{"term":"2015","caseName":"Fisher v. University of Texas","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2015/14-981","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - December 09, 2015","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/24024","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument this morning in Case 14-981, Fisher v. The University of Texas at Austin. Before we get started, I'll advise the lawyers that this is our only case this morning, so we intend to grant the parties ten minutes or so of extra time and the amicus five minutes. So Mr. Rein, no need to rush. (Laughter.)","start":0,"stop":26.595,"duration":26.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: I appreciate the extra time, and I didn't rush up here to start before you invited me this time. In reviewing the Fifth Circuit's initial decision in what we call Fisher I, seven members of this Court reaffirmed that a clear precondition to the use of race as an admissions factor was the ability to satisfy what was called the \"demanding burden of strict scrutiny\" articulated in Grutter and Bakke. By establishing that she was considered for admission to UT under a system that discriminated against her on the basis of her race, Ms. Fisher placed upon UT the burden of -- of proving, by evidence of record, that its use of race was, first, in pursuit of a compelling, constitutionally legitimate interest expressed with sufficient clarity and concreteness to allow a reviewing court to determine, first, that the use of race was a necessary last resort in pursuing the interest defined, taking into account reasonably available nonracial alternatives.","start":26.595,"stop":100.12,"duration":73.53}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rein, may I ask, if we didn't have the 10 percent plan, if that were out of this case, and all that were left were the Grutter-like plan, would you then recognize that you had no claim? We have the -- what -- what the University of Texas has added on to the 10 percent plan.","start":100.12,"stop":129.51,"duration":29.39},{"text":"But now we wipe out the 10 percent, and we have only the Grutter-like plan.","start":129.51,"stop":135.595,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- with respect, I -- I would question the premise of the question because it's not the Grutter-like plan in its entirety.","start":135.595,"stop":146.18,"duration":10.59}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"I know it's not --","start":146.18,"stop":146.59,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be a totally different --","start":146.59,"stop":147.57,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but -- but I'm asking the hypothetical.","start":147.57,"stop":149.55,"duration":1.98}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":149.55,"stop":149.94,"duration":0.39},{"text":"And I'm saying even in the AI/PAI system it's not a Grutter-like plan.","start":149.94,"stop":155.95,"duration":6.01},{"text":"It's not a plan of shaping a class by individualized one-to-one comparisons.","start":155.95,"stop":161.675,"duration":5.73},{"text":"It's not aimed at a critical mass.","start":161.675,"stop":164.79,"duration":3.11},{"text":"It's not a Grutter plan in that sense. But I think the -- the other part of this is that's, of course, not the case before us.","start":164.79,"stop":173.005,"duration":8.22},{"text":"When you look at the satisfaction of a compelling interest, you look and ask: Does my preexisting system satisfy that interest? Do I have a need to do something else? And if I have a need to do something, is that something --","start":173.005,"stop":186.89,"duration":13.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Assume need was proven. I know.","start":186.89,"stop":190.925,"duration":4.04},{"text":"You're -- you're -- you're -- we're putting aside need.","start":190.925,"stop":194.2,"duration":3.27},{"text":"What's wrong with this plan if need is put aside?","start":194.2,"stop":198.685,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's put it this way: We do not oppose the use of the various PAI factors that were in place before race was added.","start":198.685,"stop":209.745,"duration":11.06},{"text":"What's wrong with this plan, apart --","start":209.745,"stop":212.435,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no, no, no.","start":212.435,"stop":212.99,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":212.99,"stop":213.12,"duration":0.13}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I know you're saying they don't need to do it.","start":213.12,"stop":215.62,"duration":2.5},{"text":"I said put it aside and answer Justice Ginsburg's question.","start":215.62,"stop":219.94,"duration":4.32}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And I -- yes, and --","start":219.94,"stop":220.55,"duration":0.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"If they had to use race, how are they using it improperly?","start":220.55,"stop":226.025,"duration":5.47}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"If you have to use race and you want to use the model that was created in Bakke and Grutter, you would need to build profiles of individuals that would allow you to judge them one against another in the context of the class and the educational experience you are trying to create.","start":226.025,"stop":244.945,"duration":18.92}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"My God, that sounds like it's using race more rather than less than this plan does.","start":244.945,"stop":250.12,"duration":5.18}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm sorry if it sounds that way.","start":250.12,"stop":252.29,"duration":2.17},{"text":"It is not.","start":252.29,"stop":252.88,"duration":0.59},{"text":"It simply says, in a situation of the Bakke situation where you're looking at every aspect of an individual and you're trying to judge whether one or another of individuals for the -- for places, the last places would most benefit the class, the class as a whole as a learning entity, then you can, as Bakke indicates, take account of the fact that they may have different backgrounds, which would contribute different ideas.","start":252.88,"stop":279.89,"duration":27.01}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"How does that --","start":279.89,"stop":280.29,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Those are whole-person comparisons.","start":280.29,"stop":282.04,"duration":1.75},{"text":"This is not the system that -- this system doesn't do anything like Bakke. So if -- it's very different.","start":282.04,"stop":288.27,"duration":6.23},{"text":"Even if you separate it from the necessity issue -- which is, of course, a major issue in this case, but I'm assuming your question -- that they've shown that they needed to use race, there was no other way to do whatever they were trying to do -- which isn't clear to me either -- so you have both the question of whether they've defined a legitimate compelling interest; you have the question of whether they've shown any necessity to use race.","start":288.27,"stop":310.52,"duration":22.25},{"text":"But if I -- even I put those aside, whether this is the narrowly tailored vision that came out of Bakke is a very serious question.","start":310.52,"stop":318.405,"duration":7.88},{"text":"It isn't.","start":318.405,"stop":319.05,"duration":0.65},{"text":"It's quite different. And I can --","start":319.05,"stop":320.99,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You still haven't answered why this is worse than Bakke.","start":320.99,"stop":325.935,"duration":4.94},{"text":"I mean --","start":325.935,"stop":327.35,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Because it -- it's not used to build a class.","start":327.35,"stop":331.45,"duration":4.1},{"text":"It's just used to create a racial plus and to increase the number of minority admissions.","start":331.45,"stop":337.28,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"How is race given --","start":337.28,"stop":337.88,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It's race as such.","start":337.88,"stop":338.945,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"How is race given a plus? I -- I thought that what they're looking for is leaders in diversity, not just of race, but of experiences generally.","start":338.945,"stop":350.85,"duration":11.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Those factors --","start":350.85,"stop":351.87,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So how --","start":351.87,"stop":352.749,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":352.749,"stop":353.62,"duration":0.87},{"text":"But those factors were in the PAI before they added race.","start":353.62,"stop":357.45,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Leadership; demonstrated awards and success out of school; overcoming obstacles, like a single-parent family. Those were all part of the PAI before race was added. Race was just tacked on, as they said, as a factor of a factor of a factor. They've shifted position as to how it's used.","start":357.45,"stop":375.7,"duration":18.25},{"text":"In the -- in the district court, it was sort of minimized, a factor of a factor of a factor.","start":375.7,"stop":379.71,"duration":4.01},{"text":"It's a minor plus; don't worry about it.","start":379.71,"stop":381.96,"duration":2.25},{"text":"It's now become, well, it's a contextualized part of the PAS, which is part of the PAI, and we can discretionarily jack that up any way we want. But all those other factors that they claim --","start":381.96,"stop":393.5,"duration":11.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I think your brief admitted that this isn't in favor of any particular race, that white people in some situations can show leadership, as -- as well as black or Hispanic or Asian or Native American.","start":393.5,"stop":406.63,"duration":13.13},{"text":"Any race could benefit from this plus factor.","start":406.63,"stop":410.4,"duration":3.77},{"text":"So how is this --","start":410.4,"stop":411.93,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- worse than Bakke?","start":411.93,"stop":413.3,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"With respect, we did not concede that, and we would not concede it because the other PAI factors might benefit anybody of any race.","start":413.3,"stop":423.055,"duration":9.75},{"text":"People's circumstances, their leadership, their community efforts -- those are universal, and they can benefit any candidate.","start":423.055,"stop":430.235,"duration":7.18},{"text":"But they don't benefit from the race factor. The race factor was designed to benefit --","start":430.235,"stop":434.41,"duration":4.18}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But in Grutter -- in both Grutter and what Justice Powell said would be proper in Bakke, race was a factor.","start":434.41,"stop":443.93,"duration":9.52},{"text":"Race, itself, was a factor. And that's why I'm finding it very hard to distinguish what the university is doing, apart from the 10 percent plan. But let -- let me ask you about the 10 percent plan itself, because it seems to me that that is so obviously driven by one thing only, and that thing is race.","start":443.93,"stop":468.41,"duration":24.48},{"text":"It's totally dependent upon having racially segregated neighborhoods, racially segregated schools, and it operates as a disincentive for a minority student to step out of that segregated community and attempt to get an integrated education.","start":468.41,"stop":489.16,"duration":20.75}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, let -- let me respond to this, with respect, this -- this way.","start":489.16,"stop":493.595,"duration":4.44},{"text":"The Top 10 Plan does not classify anybody by race.","start":493.595,"stop":497.515,"duration":3.92},{"text":"It addresses only standing within the Texas educational system.","start":497.515,"stop":501.3,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But it could work only in the background.","start":501.3,"stop":503.91,"duration":2.61}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"When you say \"work,\" it works on a number of fronts.","start":503.91,"stop":506.66,"duration":2.75},{"text":"It creates geographic diversity. It looks all over Texas.","start":506.66,"stop":510.24,"duration":3.58},{"text":"It doesn't distinguish between high schools.","start":510.24,"stop":512.98,"duration":2.74},{"text":"It creates socioeconomic diversity.","start":512.98,"stop":515.52,"duration":2.54},{"text":"It does have an effect, a demonstrated effect on race because a number of minorities, the type they care about, are admitted under the top 10 program.","start":515.52,"stop":523.535,"duration":8.01},{"text":"But it's not based on race.","start":523.535,"stop":525.345,"duration":1.81},{"text":"It's based on the degree of effort you make relative to the other people with whom you're being --","start":525.345,"stop":530.62,"duration":5.27}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It is created because of race.","start":530.62,"stop":532.995,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm not in a position to tell you why it was created.","start":532.995,"stop":536.32,"duration":3.33},{"text":"It -- it was created --","start":536.32,"stop":537.31,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any doubt that it was created to increase the number of minority students? Was there any other reason for the 10 percent plan?","start":537.31,"stop":544.82,"duration":7.51}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I've given you other reasons, which are it's a -- it's kind of a democratic recognition that you want to invite people from all over Texas, regardless of the school they went to.","start":544.82,"stop":556.675,"duration":11.85},{"text":"You're looking for those who are trying the hardest, who are doing the best, who excel in their environment.","start":556.675,"stop":561.57,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"It was recreated in the wake of Hopwood.","start":561.57,"stop":565.365,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that timing, yes.","start":565.365,"stop":567.445,"duration":2.08}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"So I think that was the purpose, to find a neutral framework within which to satisfy the State's and the university's objectives.","start":567.445,"stop":576.675,"duration":9.23}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And certainly one in the legislature might have looked at the predictable effect, but that purpose and effect are different.","start":576.675,"stop":583.86,"duration":7.19},{"text":"But yes, it was created, and in part, because certain schools do have minorities, the idea was, well, that would benefit those schools just as it would benefit a rural high school in a white community, which ordinarily would have very great difficulty placing its students in the University of Texas.","start":583.86,"stop":600.81,"duration":16.95},{"text":"This system --","start":600.81,"stop":602.12,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"You argue that the University of Texas' goals and -- or announced goals are insufficiently concrete. Can you give an example of what, in your view, would be a sufficiently concrete criterion or set of criteria to achieve diversity?","start":602.12,"stop":622.16,"duration":20.04}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and -- and certainly, the Solicitor General's attempted to do so by breaking down the abstract goals into concrete objectives.","start":622.16,"stop":629.68,"duration":7.52},{"text":"One goal that certainly Grutter respects is, if you have studied your campus and you believe there's an inadequate exchange of views, and the minorities feel so isolated they cannot properly bring to bear their perspective on the campus, you can look at measures of how successful are we in this kind of dialogue and try to investigate that, and try to say, okay, is there a level -- you know, when do we reach a level of critical mass, which is the term in Grutter, where that exchange is vibrant and is taking place on our campus.","start":629.68,"stop":663.79,"duration":34.11},{"text":"That's one measure.","start":663.79,"stop":665.12,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but I don't understand. How do you do that?","start":665.12,"stop":667.255,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not easy to do, and it's not our job to do it.","start":667.255,"stop":670.985,"duration":3.73},{"text":"I mean, we're not here to tell them how to do it, but your -- if one wanted to endeavor to try to find this kind of concrete level, we're not saying quota, but we are saying you have to -- you, the university, if you want to use this forbidden tool, this odious classification, you've got to find a way to do it.","start":670.985,"stop":690.55,"duration":19.56},{"text":"You've got to be able to explain what your concrete objective is.","start":690.55,"stop":693.285,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Are there any critical mass studies that you can refer to? I mean, are there --","start":693.285,"stop":697.64,"duration":4.36}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"None that I know about.","start":697.64,"stop":698.22,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"-- scientific studies where you know at what point you suddenly have enough of a mass?","start":698.22,"stop":704.19,"duration":5.97}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":704.19,"stop":704.95,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And --","start":704.95,"stop":705.51,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So what did the university base it on?","start":705.51,"stop":707.25,"duration":1.74}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"The university based it on two things.","start":707.25,"stop":709.93,"duration":2.68},{"text":"It was short of the demographics of the high school graduating class, which is measurable but not legitimate, and it claimed that it was basing it on this classroom, a small-class study which they had conducted previously, which indicated that minorities were not present to the -- their satisfaction in a lot of small classes.","start":709.93,"stop":728.41,"duration":18.48},{"text":"That --","start":728.41,"stop":728.85,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Seven year -- sorry.","start":728.85,"stop":729.905,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me. To their satisfaction.","start":729.905,"stop":732,"duration":2.1},{"text":"I'm asking: On what do they base their satisfaction? On what do they base? Like, 15 percent, 20 percent?","start":732,"stop":740.76,"duration":8.76}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They premised it on good faith, and that was accepted in the Fifth Circuit on the first iteration of this case, and this Court said good faith does not suffice.","start":740.76,"stop":748.945,"duration":8.19},{"text":"So --","start":748.945,"stop":749.18,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":749.18,"stop":749.91,"duration":0.73},{"text":"I thought that the study they did showed that in 1996, they had more participation in these smaller classes.","start":749.91,"stop":762.19,"duration":12.28},{"text":"I don't know if they're really small when they're somewhere between eight and 25 people.","start":762.19,"stop":767.795,"duration":5.6},{"text":"That was a -- but there were more of those classes in 1996 than in 2003 or '2 when they were looking at that study. It would seem to me that that suggests that there's less -- what they took from it, that there's less exchange of ideas in a classroom rather than more, based on this race-neutral policy.","start":767.795,"stop":798.465,"duration":30.67}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think --","start":798.465,"stop":799.73,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What's wrong -- since you have to infer these things, you can't use a quota.","start":799.73,"stop":804.08,"duration":4.35}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me --","start":804.08,"stop":805.07,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You're saying we can't -- they can't use demographics.","start":805.07,"stop":808.31,"duration":3.24},{"text":"So they use a study that shows there's less classes.","start":808.31,"stop":813.21,"duration":4.9},{"text":"There's less people in classes.","start":813.21,"stop":815.69,"duration":2.48},{"text":"They talk to administrators, faculty, and students.","start":815.69,"stop":819.785,"duration":4.09},{"text":"They're having racial incidents on campus where students of color are complaining that they feel isolated, that stereotyping is going on, on campus. What more do they need?","start":819.785,"stop":837.94,"duration":18.16}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me start with your first concern, which is this classroom study. First thing I would observe about that if I were in their position, and I'm not, is that the second study was done at a time when there were more minorities admitted than the first study, and they claimed it went backwards.","start":837.94,"stop":855.38,"duration":17.44},{"text":"So that might tell me right away that the problem -- the necessity for using race could not be demonstrated for that, because when you --","start":855.38,"stop":862.45,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":862.45,"stop":862.61,"duration":0.16},{"text":"Because the -- the necessity is not the necessity you're talking about. It's the -- as I read it.","start":862.61,"stop":868.545,"duration":5.93},{"text":"I mean, you use words like \"critical mass\" and so forth.","start":868.545,"stop":872.62,"duration":4.08},{"text":"It sounds like a cloud of sort of you don't know what they're talking, but as I read further into it, it becomes quite specific, that is, 75 percent of the students are at this university because they were in the top 10 percent of their class. And it doesn't take long before students and faculty in particular situations know who is who.","start":872.62,"stop":896.66,"duration":24.04},{"text":"25 percent of the students in that class are admitted; they're good students, not in the top 10 percent on the basis of leadership, activities, awards, work experience, community service, family's economic status, school status, family responsibilities, single-parent home, languages other than English spoken at home, SAT score relative to school's average, and race occasionally, too. Okay? We're talking about that 25 percent.","start":896.66,"stop":923.645,"duration":26.99},{"text":"And it won't take long before students in a class see that in that 25 percent, which means you aren't just in the top 10 percent of your class, in that 25 percent there is hardly anybody who is African-American or Hispanic.","start":923.645,"stop":942.319,"duration":18.67},{"text":"And the -- and seven years of experience with that kind of thing led the faculty at meetings, administrators, and others to say, we should do more to see that that 25 percent has occasionally somebody who is a minority.","start":942.319,"stop":960.575,"duration":18.26}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Does anybody but the faculty --","start":960.575,"stop":962.16,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what their program is.","start":962.16,"stop":963.53,"duration":1.37},{"text":"It isn't something like critical mass, et cetera. And -- and -- and if you have to say, it seems to me, why is that not a diversity-related judgment of what is necessary?","start":963.53,"stop":977.495,"duration":13.97}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"So, Justice Breyer, let me answer that. First of all, one thing your question establishes quite clearly is if one assumes premises from evidence that doesn't exist, you can draw conclusions that are perhaps invalid. So let me go back to -- to where you started.","start":977.495,"stop":991.71,"duration":14.22},{"text":"You say these people are admitted on the basis of the various PAI factors, which you read.","start":991.71,"stop":996.55,"duration":4.84},{"text":"That's not how they're admitted.","start":996.55,"stop":998.26,"duration":1.71},{"text":"That PAI is only part of the admissions criteria.","start":998.26,"stop":1000.94,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1000.94,"stop":1001.23,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's not truly holistic because in the holistic systems, you look at the person as a whole.","start":1001.23,"stop":1006.06,"duration":4.83},{"text":"Here you could have the most wonderful PAI and never come close to admission, because they use the AI independently.","start":1006.06,"stop":1013.105,"duration":7.05},{"text":"So they're not admitted --","start":1013.105,"stop":1014.1,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Every school is like that. Every school in the country that's a college that I've ever experienced is a combination of grades, class position, and a lot of other things.","start":1014.1,"stop":1024.155,"duration":10.05}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"But --","start":1024.155,"stop":1024.37,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"So I'm talking about people who aren't admitted; 75 percent are, solely on the basis of class ranking.","start":1024.37,"stop":1031.145,"duration":6.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":1031.145,"stop":1031.34,"duration":0.19},{"text":"And -- and then you assume that people could identify them one from another. They're --","start":1031.34,"stop":1035.055,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I was going to ask that. Does anybody, except the faculty, know who this elite 25 percent is?","start":1035.055,"stop":1041.12,"duration":6.06}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1041.12,"stop":1041.44,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"And all of the 10 percent people identified themselves?","start":1041.44,"stop":1045,"duration":3.56}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1045,"stop":1045.36,"duration":0.36},{"text":"They do not.","start":1045.36,"stop":1045.65,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They go around in bunches, hey, I'm one of the 10 percent?","start":1045.65,"stop":1047.77,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They don't, and --","start":1047.77,"stop":1048.54,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They don't know who the 10 percent are, do they?","start":1048.54,"stop":1050.155,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and the level of admission to the faculty at the university subgroup in which they study, whether it's business or communications, there it's all done by AI/PAI.","start":1050.155,"stop":1060.57,"duration":10.41},{"text":"They're all --","start":1060.57,"stop":1061.05,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I --","start":1061.05,"stop":1061.55,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They're all done equally.","start":1061.55,"stop":1062.56,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I come back to the issue of classroom diversity? Because that does seem to me to be something that could be measured.","start":1062.56,"stop":1070.88,"duration":8.32},{"text":"And maybe there's evidence in the record that measures it.","start":1070.88,"stop":1073.75,"duration":2.87},{"text":"I don't know.","start":1073.75,"stop":1074.18,"duration":0.43},{"text":"So that's what I want to ask you.","start":1074.18,"stop":1075.55,"duration":1.37},{"text":"But the University knows which students, even if -- assuming that the students don't know, this University knows which students were admitted because they were in the top 10 percent and which were not. And presumably they have a record of all of the classes and which students enrolled in which classes.","start":1075.55,"stop":1095.745,"duration":20.19},{"text":"And so it would seem to me to be possible to determine whether the students who were admitted under the 10 percent plan were less likely to choose to enroll in the classes in which minorities are underrepresented than the students who were admitted under holistic review.","start":1095.745,"stop":1114.76,"duration":19.02},{"text":"Now, maybe that's in the record.","start":1114.76,"stop":1116.14,"duration":1.38},{"text":"I haven't found it.","start":1116.14,"stop":1117.07,"duration":0.93},{"text":"Is there anything in the record to show that?","start":1117.07,"stop":1118.99,"duration":1.92}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"The best of the record, because they didn't study that specifically.","start":1118.99,"stop":1122.11,"duration":3.12},{"text":"When they did the classroom study, they -- they did not try to distinguish who was in the class.","start":1122.11,"stop":1126.9,"duration":4.79},{"text":"It was just a number count by -- by classification, how many minorities of this kind, how many of that kind.","start":1126.9,"stop":1132.3,"duration":5.4},{"text":"They counted African-Americans. They counted Hispanic students, or -- and they counted Asians in that study, but they counted them by race.","start":1132.3,"stop":1140.29,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't want -- I don't want to pre-demit this line of questioning because I think it's important and we're well into the substantive issues. May I begin with almost a procedural point: Did you object to the University's request that this case be remanded to the district court?","start":1140.29,"stop":1157.79,"duration":17.5}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"We did in -- in the Fifth Circuit.","start":1157.79,"stop":1159.72,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Fifth Circuit. It does seem to me, as Justice Alito's question, and frankly some of the other questions have indicated, that the litigants, and frankly this Court, have been denied the advantage and the perspective that would be gained if there would be additional fact-finding under the instructions that Fisher sought to give.","start":1159.72,"stop":1186.07,"duration":26.35},{"text":"And that just -- we're just arguing the same case.","start":1186.07,"stop":1189.4,"duration":3.33}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":1189.4,"stop":1189.91,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"It's as if nothing had happened.","start":1189.91,"stop":1191.82,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and the reason for that --","start":1191.82,"stop":1193.52,"duration":1.7}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And I -- it seems to me that Justice Alito's question indicates that this is the kind of thing that we should know but we don't know.","start":1193.52,"stop":1202.985,"duration":9.46}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let -- let me point out that the -- the purpose of strict scrutiny is not just to adjudicate.","start":1202.985,"stop":1208.365,"duration":5.38},{"text":"It is to instruct the University that before you use the odious classification, before you employ race, you ought to know these things.","start":1208.365,"stop":1216,"duration":7.63},{"text":"If you're going to depend on them, you ought to study them and know them.","start":1216,"stop":1219.065,"duration":3.07},{"text":"So the failure to do that so there is no evidence is not just because they didn't put it in --","start":1219.065,"stop":1224.13,"duration":5.07}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But they weren't given the chance to add additional evidence in order to meet that standard.","start":1224.13,"stop":1228.65,"duration":4.52}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they can't go back and recreate the past.","start":1228.65,"stop":1231.175,"duration":2.52},{"text":"They can't -- they have put in all the evidence available to them about --","start":1231.175,"stop":1234.67,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But they could answer some of the questions as -- like the ones Justice Alito added.","start":1234.67,"stop":1239.88,"duration":5.21},{"text":"And I think it's a very important point.","start":1239.88,"stop":1243.23,"duration":3.35}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They could -- I mean, but they'd have to go back and study the conditions at the time they made the decision.","start":1243.23,"stop":1250.445,"duration":7.21},{"text":"And I think that the failure to do that kind of thing indicates that the retreat to race was reflexive; was done on the day Grutter came down.","start":1250.445,"stop":1258.24,"duration":7.8}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Not only that.","start":1258.24,"stop":1258.99,"duration":0.75},{"text":"Also the failure to put it in.","start":1258.99,"stop":1261.04,"duration":2.05},{"text":"It was their burden to put it in, wasn't it?","start":1261.04,"stop":1263.625,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1263.625,"stop":1264.04,"duration":0.41},{"text":"And they knew that --","start":1264.04,"stop":1264.6,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So we're going to say, oh, they failed to put it in.","start":1264.6,"stop":1266.63,"duration":2.03},{"text":"Let's give them another chance.","start":1266.63,"stop":1268.565,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, procedurally --","start":1268.565,"stop":1269.39,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's do a do-over.","start":1269.39,"stop":1270.71,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They --","start":1270.71,"stop":1271,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Send it back down so they can now put in what they should have put in in order to prevail the first time around.","start":1271,"stop":1276.74,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And that I -- I entirely agree with that.","start":1276.74,"stop":1279.74,"duration":3},{"text":"And in -- in fairness, they knew that the standard was strict scrutiny.","start":1279.74,"stop":1282.78,"duration":3.04},{"text":"Grutter had said strict scrutiny.","start":1282.78,"stop":1284.27,"duration":1.49},{"text":"Bakke said strict scrutiny.","start":1284.27,"stop":1285.825,"duration":1.56},{"text":"It was no surprise. And Justice Alito, more directly, the evidence we did find in the record indicated that where the most selective schools were concerned, which would then lead you to the smaller classes, more of the Top Ten minorities enrolled in that than the added minorities that they derived --","start":1285.825,"stop":1301.58,"duration":15.75}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the issue in this case is not whether the University can have holistic review.","start":1301.58,"stop":1307.265,"duration":5.69}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1307.265,"stop":1307.87,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The issue is whether they can have as a component of holistic review after they have taken into account other characteristics that are not dependent on race; they can add race as an additional characteristic. And so if it were -- is there -- would there be any way of determining, if there were a remand, which of the non-top 10 admittees were admitted solely because of race? In other words, these students would not have been admitted taking into account leadership and family, education and socioeconomic background and hardship and everything else.","start":1307.87,"stop":1342.16,"duration":34.29}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"According to the University of Texas, the answer to that is no.","start":1342.16,"stop":1345.115,"duration":2.95},{"text":"They cannot make that determination because, in their view, race is contextual.","start":1345.115,"stop":1352.085,"duration":6.97},{"text":"You cannot sort out those who could have made it without race from those who didn't. And -- and just in response to Justice Breyer, as fact of record, prior to the invocation of race, 15 percent of the non-top 10 admits were -- were the minorities who later benefitted from race. So it was not devoid of admits who were Hispanic or -- or African-American.","start":1352.085,"stop":1377.03,"duration":24.94},{"text":"It was producing 15 percent, a marginal increase out of race was, if you try to measure it, very small.","start":1377.03,"stop":1384.115,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And -- and I could think of reasons for that, but -- so they couldn't put that in. They denied that you could ever identify those students. So that would be a fruitless pursuit unless they completely change everything they said before.","start":1384.115,"stop":1395.78,"duration":11.66}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask --","start":1395.78,"stop":1396.28,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you associate a number with \"the very small\"? I guess it would be the number of students who were admitted with the consideration of race who were not also --","start":1396.28,"stop":1406.625,"duration":10.35}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":1406.625,"stop":1407.21,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":1407.21,"stop":1407.35,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That would be the measurement. And -- and there's no perfect answer to that when the University says they can't identify them.","start":1407.35,"stop":1412.54,"duration":5.19},{"text":"But what we did is we looked at the historic period in which they were using the PAI, without reference to race, and compared that to the percentage admitted of the total student body of those admits in the period when they were using race, and they compare -- this is about a two and a half percent difference, so it's very small.","start":1412.54,"stop":1430.82,"duration":18.28},{"text":"And you would --","start":1430.82,"stop":1431.24,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Two and a half percent difference in entering class numbers or number of minorities admitted?","start":1431.24,"stop":1437.665,"duration":6.42}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Number of minorities.","start":1437.665,"stop":1439.17,"duration":1.51},{"text":"You can measure it either way by enrollment or admission.","start":1439.17,"stop":1441.69,"duration":2.52},{"text":"It's still going to be a very small number.","start":1441.69,"stop":1443.75,"duration":2.06},{"text":"It doesn't make -- it's statistically lost.","start":1443.75,"stop":1446.445,"duration":2.69},{"text":"So it's a very small increment.","start":1446.445,"stop":1448.54,"duration":2.1},{"text":"And of course, you --","start":1448.54,"stop":1450.12,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The number is important to me.","start":1450.12,"stop":1452.19,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Is it -- is what any --","start":1452.19,"stop":1453.81,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It's under 3 --","start":1453.81,"stop":1454.75,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I can ask your friend on the other side, but --","start":1454.75,"stop":1456.685,"duration":1.93}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It's under 3 percent.","start":1456.685,"stop":1458.33,"duration":1.64}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Of what? Of numbers --","start":1458.33,"stop":1459.74,"duration":1.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Of total admits or the -- and the total enrollees both.","start":1459.74,"stop":1463.125,"duration":3.38},{"text":"And Judge Garza actually premised it.","start":1463.125,"stop":1465.8,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the minority students. Of blacks.","start":1465.8,"stop":1468.39,"duration":2.59}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Of the class itself.","start":1468.39,"stop":1469.89,"duration":1.5},{"text":"So what percentage of -- yes.","start":1469.89,"stop":1472.97,"duration":3.08},{"text":"Let me be very clear.","start":1472.97,"stop":1474.2,"duration":1.23},{"text":"What you're trying to measure is to what extent did the use of race boost over the use of the PAI on a nonracial basis.","start":1474.2,"stop":1482.11,"duration":7.91}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1482.11,"stop":1482.52,"duration":0.41},{"text":"I thought you said --","start":1482.52,"stop":1482.84,"duration":0.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But in Parents -- in Parents Involved, you indicated that at some point the actual benefit of the program turns out to be not really worth the very difficult decision to allow race to be considered if at the end of the day it generates a certain number.","start":1482.84,"stop":1499.01,"duration":16.17},{"text":"And I'm trying to figure out what that number is.","start":1499.01,"stop":1500.7,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and I am saying that, as we said in our briefs, and we tried to -- there's no perfect measurement because you don't have them running simultaneously.","start":1500.7,"stop":1508.07,"duration":7.37}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1508.07,"stop":1508.22,"duration":0.15},{"text":"Right.","start":1508.22,"stop":1508.43,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"But if you tried to do it by looking at the results when using the PAI, but not race, versus the results both at the admission and enrollment stage of using the PAI affected by race, it's a -- it's under 3 percent.","start":1508.43,"stop":1522.73,"duration":14.3},{"text":"And it's again --","start":1522.73,"stop":1523.59,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1523.59,"stop":1523.89,"duration":0.3},{"text":"I'm not sure where you get that number.","start":1523.89,"stop":1525.745,"duration":1.85},{"text":"As I look at it, between 2004 and 2006 -- '7, it nearly doubled from 3.6 of the holistic class to 6.8.","start":1525.745,"stop":1538.71,"duration":12.97},{"text":"For Hispanic students -- that's for blacks -- it went from 11.6 to 16.9.","start":1538.71,"stop":1545.17,"duration":6.46},{"text":"I don't think that's -- that small a change. In 2008, two -- 20 percent of all black students and 15 percent of all Hispanic students were offered admission through holistic review.","start":1545.17,"stop":1562.89,"duration":17.72},{"text":"Black and Hispanic admission and enrollment rates have increased since 2005.","start":1562.89,"stop":1569.08,"duration":6.19},{"text":"This is on -- on holistic review.","start":1569.08,"stop":1571.58,"duration":2.5},{"text":"The only exception was 2008, and that was because 92 percent of the class came in under the 10 percent plan.","start":1571.58,"stop":1579.6,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you know --","start":1579.6,"stop":1580.495,"duration":0.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"When your number --","start":1580.495,"stop":1581.48,"duration":0.99}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- when you -- when you use numbers about --","start":1581.48,"stop":1583.29,"duration":1.81}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that's not small.","start":1583.29,"stop":1583.89,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- admission on holistic review, that incorporates the ones who would have made it without race, so it's not a valid comparative number.","start":1583.89,"stop":1590.945,"duration":7.05}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The ones who would -- the ones who would have made it --","start":1590.945,"stop":1593.7,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- without race are incorporated in, quote, \"holistic review.\" So those numbers really don't tell you anything about the effect of race.","start":1593.7,"stop":1600.79,"duration":7.09},{"text":"They don't --","start":1600.79,"stop":1601.01,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wait a minute.","start":1601.01,"stop":1601.59,"duration":0.58},{"text":"I don't understand how that can be.","start":1601.59,"stop":1603.625,"duration":2.04},{"text":"If the 2004 number was that much lower than the 2007 number, race has to have some input in that fact -- in that --","start":1603.625,"stop":1615.61,"duration":11.98}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it has some effect.","start":1615.61,"stop":1616.84,"duration":1.23},{"text":"That's what UT says.","start":1616.84,"stop":1618,"duration":1.16},{"text":"They haven't measured, and say they can't measure the effect.","start":1618,"stop":1620.91,"duration":2.91},{"text":"You're dealing with different classes.","start":1620.91,"stop":1622.625,"duration":1.71}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I ask you a different question now? I fear something.","start":1622.625,"stop":1629.05,"duration":6.42},{"text":"I know there is an educational debate on the benefits and costs of a 10 percent plan.","start":1629.05,"stop":1636.9,"duration":7.85},{"text":"I don't want to get into that debate, but I do have a worry, which is: If you're reading proof of a compelling need, or proof of a compelling need, will any holistic review ever survive? Because as I'm reading your answer, to narrowly tailor, schools have to use nonracial means of doing it.","start":1636.9,"stop":1666.64,"duration":29.74},{"text":"And if the 10 percent plan is the only thing that achieves a greater number in minorities, won't every school have to use a 10 percent plan?","start":1666.64,"stop":1677.47,"duration":10.83}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"We're not, certainly, trying to dictate that every school use a 10 percent plan, nor is it the only way in which you can encourage and increase minority enrollment.","start":1677.47,"stop":1687.005,"duration":9.54},{"text":"So I -- I don't accept that premise. Strict scrutiny is a -- a heavy burden.","start":1687.005,"stop":1693.81,"duration":6.8},{"text":"And the purpose of strict scrutiny as to recognize that the base --","start":1693.81,"stop":1696.97,"duration":3.16}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So your answer is yes. If there's no other --","start":1696.97,"stop":1698.83,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1698.83,"stop":1698.93,"duration":0.1},{"text":"I --","start":1698.93,"stop":1698.96,"duration":0.03}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- way of doing it, then the only other race-neutral way -- if offering scholarships, which this university did, increasing outreach to minority neighborhoods, they did and continue to do -- there's a list of about six or eight other things they did that didn't increase the admission of minorities.","start":1698.96,"stop":1723.87,"duration":24.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"There are many other things they could do.","start":1723.87,"stop":1726.56,"duration":2.69},{"text":"We're not trying to tell them how to run it. I mean, clearly one of the things they could do is -- even in the PAI, they recognize that by emphasizing, as they did at first, the two essay scores, which are strictly composition, grammar, that -- that is as culturally biased as you can get it.","start":1726.56,"stop":1743.08,"duration":16.52},{"text":"It -- it makes it difficult for those who have gone through an inferior secondary program to excel. So they cut that score to three.","start":1743.08,"stop":1750.39,"duration":7.31},{"text":"They could cut it to two.","start":1750.39,"stop":1751.755,"duration":1.37},{"text":"They could -- they could take measures which were aimed at looking at potential deficiencies in initial education because you come from a home where there isn't a college-educated person and say, we're going to take those further into account because they apply equally without regard to race. So there are many things they could do with --","start":1751.755,"stop":1770.89,"duration":19.13}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, but that's exactly the question, I think.","start":1770.89,"stop":1773.54,"duration":2.65},{"text":"I would -- I can put the same question -- or suppose we do send it back to the district court and, put in more evidence, we tell them. Suppose we did that.","start":1773.54,"stop":1785.85,"duration":12.31},{"text":"And suppose they start with the basic plan where we want to use race is in the 25 percent of the holistic area.","start":1785.85,"stop":1794.33,"duration":8.48},{"text":"We want to do that. Now, there -- you've seen the chart -- and I've seen the chart -- of the factors that are one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven, twelve.","start":1794.33,"stop":1804.61,"duration":10.28},{"text":"You know, you've seen that chart.","start":1804.61,"stop":1805.84,"duration":1.23},{"text":"I've seen the chart.","start":1805.84,"stop":1806.79,"duration":0.95},{"text":"And at the bottom of the chart in my list is the word \"race.\" It says \"race,\" r-a-c-e. Okay? What kind of evidence, in your opinion, could they or anyone else with any roughly similar plan put in that would show, in your view, that this is constitutional?","start":1806.79,"stop":1828.6,"duration":21.81}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, you have the example of Justice Powell's opinion in Bakke.","start":1828.6,"stop":1832.45,"duration":3.85},{"text":"And that says that if you're looking at the whole person and you're comparing individuals one to another to say who will best suit the educational need of the class, then you take account of a person's race.","start":1832.45,"stop":1843.8,"duration":11.35},{"text":"It's part of the -- the exercise. You don't isolate it, because if you look at Justice Bakke's example, he's got A and B, two minority African-American students, and C.","start":1843.8,"stop":1853.62,"duration":9.82},{"text":"And he says, depending where the class stands in the overall composition of this learning entity, you might choose A under one circumstance; vice versa, you might choose B; and sometimes you'll choose C without regard to race. So he's looking at it as a way of looking at the totality of a person, all of their achievements, academic and otherwise. So you -- so Bakke's systems are not at issue here, nor is the top 10 at issue.","start":1853.62,"stop":1877.1,"duration":23.48},{"text":"That's -- that was accepted in this case.","start":1877.1,"stop":1879.04,"duration":1.94},{"text":"No one challenged it. So I'm saying you don't have to do the top 10.","start":1879.04,"stop":1882.22,"duration":3.18},{"text":"You can --","start":1882.22,"stop":1882.37,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":1882.37,"stop":1882.59,"duration":0.22},{"text":"So we have one. But I'm looking --","start":1882.59,"stop":1884.37,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Breyer, you can achieve this small increment of under 3 percent, in our view, by a number of alternatives that would -- would -- would give this same boost.","start":1884.37,"stop":1892.61,"duration":8.24},{"text":"These are the race -- racially alternative neutral alternatives.","start":1892.61,"stop":1895.14,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I have one.","start":1895.14,"stop":1895.905,"duration":0.76},{"text":"I have one.","start":1895.905,"stop":1896.32,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"But not --","start":1896.32,"stop":1896.61,"duration":0.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying is you should look at the two folders, and as a kind of tiebreaker, use race.","start":1896.61,"stop":1902.275,"duration":5.67},{"text":"That, to you, is okay. Now, is there -- you said there is several others? It would be helpful if you -- if you can summarize them in a sentence, so I get an idea of what the others are.","start":1902.275,"stop":1910.525,"duration":8.25}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"You could -- you could give more emphasis to the socioeconomic factors in the school.","start":1910.525,"stop":1914.31,"duration":3.78}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not to use race. I'm saying r-a-c-e, race.","start":1914.31,"stop":1918.67,"duration":4.36},{"text":"I want to know which are the things they could do that, in your view, would be okay. Because I'm really trying to find out.","start":1918.67,"stop":1925.895,"duration":7.22},{"text":"Not fatal in fact, we've said.","start":1925.895,"stop":1929.385,"duration":3.49},{"text":"Okay? Not fatal in fact.","start":1929.385,"stop":1931.95,"duration":2.57},{"text":"Fine. What are the things, in your view, that they could do so it is not fatal in fact?","start":1931.95,"stop":1938.54,"duration":6.59}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And what I've said first is they could shape their system more toward the Bakke system, and move toward individualized consideration.","start":1938.54,"stop":1945.41,"duration":6.87},{"text":"That's one thing.","start":1945.41,"stop":1946.77,"duration":1.36},{"text":"That's not fatal in fact, because this Court endorsed the -- the view that Justice Powell took of the Harvard system in Bakke.","start":1946.77,"stop":1953.73,"duration":6.96},{"text":"So that's one. They could expand the top 10.","start":1953.73,"stop":1957.015,"duration":3.29},{"text":"That's another alternative.","start":1957.015,"stop":1958.425,"duration":1.41},{"text":"That's -- that's available. They could -- as I said, they could rescore some of this --","start":1958.425,"stop":1963.29,"duration":4.87}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the top 10, you said it doesn't use race.","start":1963.29,"stop":1965.88,"duration":2.59},{"text":"Justice Breyer is asking, you say yes, race can be a factor.","start":1965.88,"stop":1971.055,"duration":5.17},{"text":"It was a factor in Bakke. It was a factor in Grutter.","start":1971.055,"stop":1975.505,"duration":4.45},{"text":"And so far, you're saying that now it can be a factor only if what? I mean, we're not talking about so-called neutral factors.","start":1975.505,"stop":1987.175,"duration":11.67},{"text":"We're talking about --","start":1987.175,"stop":1988.15,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, the first question is, you know, why are you using it? The why. Therefore, it can be a factor.","start":1988.15,"stop":1993.63,"duration":5.48},{"text":"You have to clarify the objective, you have to show the necessity, and you have to show that, if you, as -- as they do, live with and accept, over time, a very small increment in a very small segment of the class, that you can't get it done any other way.","start":1993.63,"stop":2007.545,"duration":13.91}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Because race is not the baseline. It's an odious classification.","start":2007.545,"stop":2011.245,"duration":3.7},{"text":"That's where we differ.","start":2011.245,"stop":2012.22,"duration":0.98}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"As I understand what you're saying, the Bakke approach -- comparing two individuals and -- and -- and, where they're tied, giving a -- a benefit to one for race -- that's okay.","start":2012.22,"stop":2026.39,"duration":14.17},{"text":"Regardless of whether there are any other means --","start":2026.39,"stop":2030.245,"duration":3.85}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No --","start":2030.245,"stop":2030.705,"duration":0.46}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"-- of achieving the -- the racial balance that you're looking for.","start":2030.705,"stop":2035.29,"duration":4.59},{"text":"Right?","start":2035.29,"stop":2035.69,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Justice Powell indicated in Bakke that that approach could be used where it's part of a greater function form in the class.","start":2035.69,"stop":2043.17,"duration":7.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Understand.","start":2043.17,"stop":2043.66,"duration":0.49},{"text":"Understand. But --","start":2043.66,"stop":2044.09,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And that -- and the Court has --","start":2044.09,"stop":2045.32,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But you -- you don't --","start":2045.32,"stop":2045.71,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- apparently accepted.","start":2045.71,"stop":2046.26,"duration":0.55},{"text":"We're not challenging it here.","start":2046.26,"stop":2047.43,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't have to apply the question whether it could possibly be done in any other way.","start":2047.43,"stop":2053.83,"duration":6.4},{"text":"But you're saying anything beyond that, anything else, you have to establish first that it couldn't be done another way that doesn't take into account race, such as expanding the 10 -- top 10 percent to the top 15 percent.","start":2053.83,"stop":2068.05,"duration":14.22}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That is correct.","start":2068.05,"stop":2068.84,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Right?","start":2068.84,"stop":2068.93,"duration":0.09}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And it's not just me, Justice Scalia.","start":2068.93,"stop":2071.21,"duration":2.28},{"text":"That's what this Court said in the prior opinion.","start":2071.21,"stop":2073.92,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what I thought.","start":2073.92,"stop":2074.955,"duration":1.03}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They had -- it has to be shown to be necessary. And of course, that's true of all strict scrutiny.","start":2074.955,"stop":2079.21,"duration":4.26},{"text":"And the Court said in the prior opinion that it's other strict scrutiny opinions, such as Adarand, were applicable here.","start":2079.21,"stop":2085.28,"duration":6.07},{"text":"This is not detached.","start":2085.28,"stop":2086.39,"duration":1.11},{"text":"It's not different. Strict scrutiny is a heavy burden.","start":2086.39,"stop":2089.44,"duration":3.05},{"text":"There's no question about it.","start":2089.44,"stop":2090.8,"duration":1.36},{"text":"That's why it's strict scrutiny.","start":2090.8,"stop":2092.67,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Is there any evidence that the holistic review being used by UT operates as a quota?","start":2092.67,"stop":2099.355,"duration":6.68}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- you know, I'm -- we have not claimed that, but since so much of it is masked and hidden -- but -- but if -- certainly if you're motivated, as they said, by demographics, they want to get the number up, it's certainly number-driven. And if you look at -- one thing this Court said in Grutter, you have to have a basis to review this, because you would like to make it end.","start":2099.355,"stop":2121.34,"duration":21.99},{"text":"There has to be an end point.","start":2121.34,"stop":2122.89,"duration":1.55},{"text":"So in -- if you can't find your objectives, you have no endpoint. But more important, you look at what are they looking at.","start":2122.89,"stop":2127.9,"duration":5.01},{"text":"What are they measuring each year? And they're measuring numbers.","start":2127.9,"stop":2130.87,"duration":2.97},{"text":"They want those numbers to go up.","start":2130.87,"stop":2133.195,"duration":2.33},{"text":"That's what they care about.","start":2133.195,"stop":2134.695,"duration":1.5},{"text":"That's what this system does. So whether it's a quota in the strict sense, to wit, we have a -- a definite target, their target may be equating with the population -- the high school population.","start":2134.695,"stop":2146.75,"duration":12.05},{"text":"I mean, today they're a majority-minority campus, the real world.","start":2146.75,"stop":2150.49,"duration":3.74},{"text":"They've -- they've gone because -- just because of the -- the -- the demographics of high school.","start":2150.49,"stop":2154.38,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rein, because your time is running out, there is one preliminary question I'd like you to address, and that is: What is the relief you're seeking? I take it not injunctive, because Ms. Fisher has graduated.","start":2154.38,"stop":2169.24,"duration":14.86}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2169.24,"stop":2169.755,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"And you have no class. So what -- what specific relief are you seeking in this case?","start":2169.755,"stop":2177.274,"duration":7.52}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"This case started with a plea for damages.","start":2177.274,"stop":2179.995,"duration":2.72},{"text":"The damages plea is live.","start":2179.995,"stop":2182.105,"duration":2.11},{"text":"It has never been challenged.","start":2182.105,"stop":2183.47,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But what do the damages consist of?","start":2183.47,"stop":2185.31,"duration":1.84}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They were -- the damages consisted of a -- a refund of the unjustly-committed fee for application.","start":2185.31,"stop":2192.62,"duration":7.31},{"text":"That was the direct -- one specified application.","start":2192.62,"stop":2195.97,"duration":3.35},{"text":"We also asked for other just and further relief, because at that point of the case, we didn't know anything for certain; to wit, if she was admitted, it would be one thing.","start":2195.97,"stop":2204.535,"duration":8.57},{"text":"If she wasn't -- weren't admitted, there would be other damages arising from her failure to be admitted.","start":2204.535,"stop":2210.2,"duration":5.66},{"text":"And we realized that was a separate issue.","start":2210.2,"stop":2212.27,"duration":2.07},{"text":"We reserved on it.","start":2212.27,"stop":2213.19,"duration":0.92},{"text":"We -- we've --","start":2213.19,"stop":2213.64,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"If the -- if the university should say, okay, the application fee and whatever else we add to that, we -- we offer that so that this contest will be over; if they offered you the damages that you are seeking, would the case become moot?","start":2213.64,"stop":2236.46,"duration":22.82}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2236.46,"stop":2237.225,"duration":0.76},{"text":"And the reason is the damages we are seeking were broader than that.","start":2237.225,"stop":2242.77,"duration":5.55},{"text":"That was the specific item of damage that was pleaded.","start":2242.77,"stop":2245.26,"duration":2.49},{"text":"They didn't challenge it under 12(b)(6).","start":2245.26,"stop":2247.46,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What are --","start":2247.46,"stop":2247.67,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"They answered --","start":2247.67,"stop":2248.29,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"-- what are the broad -- what are the broader? You gave me the application fee.","start":2248.29,"stop":2250.42,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, now, Ms. Fisher has not been admitted, and that she has suffered the consequences of nonadmission, which include she went to an alternative university; she had to travel as opposed to being in her home State.","start":2250.42,"stop":2261.375,"duration":10.95},{"text":"There is certainly good information that within the State of Texas, a degree from the University of Texas has consequences and earnings down the road, and that's measurable.","start":2261.375,"stop":2271.125,"duration":9.75},{"text":"And she doesn't have that benefit. All of those elements, which were not part of the case originally, because we were trying to enjoin in a way that would have her admitted, now she's not admitted.","start":2271.125,"stop":2282.09,"duration":10.97},{"text":"That changes the complexion of the case. That's why we bifurcated -- that's why we reserved the right to amend within our broader plea for all other just and relief. So in terms of just standing, we have an existing claim.","start":2282.09,"stop":2293.94,"duration":11.85},{"text":"They haven't paid us.","start":2293.94,"stop":2295.645,"duration":1.7},{"text":"They threatened to do that on the first Petition for Cert.","start":2295.645,"stop":2299.84,"duration":4.2},{"text":"They never did it.","start":2299.84,"stop":2300.53,"duration":0.69},{"text":"They didn't tender it.","start":2300.53,"stop":2301.675,"duration":1.14},{"text":"We have an existing claim.","start":2301.675,"stop":2302.83,"duration":1.15},{"text":"We have broader claims that are inchoate, because we haven't yet reached the stage of litigating remedy and damages.","start":2302.83,"stop":2309.72,"duration":6.89},{"text":"So the case continues.","start":2309.72,"stop":2311.555,"duration":1.84},{"text":"There is standing -- unquestioned standing in this case. Thank you, Your Honor.","start":2311.555,"stop":2315.19,"duration":3.64}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I suppose -- I suppose if they tender it, you don't have to accept it either, right?","start":2315.19,"stop":2318.22,"duration":3.03}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":2318.22,"stop":2319.455,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Counsel.","start":2319.455,"stop":2321.05,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"I'll reserve the rest of my time.","start":2321.05,"stop":2323.809,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Garre.","start":2323.809,"stop":2326.235,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: To pick up on the questions this morning, I'd like to focus on three things.","start":2326.235,"stop":2332.605,"duration":6.37},{"text":"One, why the record supports the Texas legislature's conclusion in 2009 that the holistic plan at issue was a necessary complement to the State's Top 10 Percent Law; two, why the record shows that Texas's holistic policy has had a meaningful impact on diversity at the University of Texas; and, three, why the record absolutely forecloses any claim that University of Texas has adopted a quota. With respect to the first question of necessity, there are three principle ways in which the record shows that the plan at issue was a necessary complement.","start":2332.605,"stop":2366.855,"duration":34.25},{"text":"First, as Justice Breyer mentioned, there is a significant portion of the admissions pool, all out-of-state students, all students from Texas high schools that don't rank, some of the best high schools in the State, and all students just below the top 10 percent who are nevertheless great students who aren't eligible for admission under the top 10 percent at all. And the Fifth Circuit found that without the consideration of race in the mix for those students, admissions would approach an all white enterprise. Secondly, the record in this case shows --","start":2366.855,"stop":2396.07,"duration":29.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":2396.07,"stop":2396.74,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Just the admissions of people beyond the top 10 percent?","start":2396.74,"stop":2400.9,"duration":4.16}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, which is an important component of the class, Your Honor. Second, and I think this goes to your point, Justice --","start":2400.9,"stop":2406.06,"duration":5.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on that point, can you determine which of the holistic admittees would not have been admitted if race was not added to the -- to the determination?","start":2406.06,"stop":2415.965,"duration":9.91}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2415.965,"stop":2416.4,"duration":0.43},{"text":"This goes to the meaningful impact point, and I think there are several ways to address it, Justice Alito. First, what you can do is you can look in the increase in African-American and Hispanic holistic admissions after the consideration of race was added. And what you find is, is that in each year, 2005, 2006, 2007, the percentage of African-American and Hispanics admitted and enrolled under the holistic plan grew.","start":2416.4,"stop":2445.22,"duration":28.82},{"text":"In fact, there was a 70 percent --","start":2445.22,"stop":2446.54,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"That's not really my question.","start":2446.54,"stop":2447.53,"duration":0.99},{"text":"My question was if you look at an individual person, can you tell whether that person was admitted because -- solely because of race? Whether that person would not have been admitted were it not for the fact that the person was an African-American or Hispanic?","start":2447.53,"stop":2461.18,"duration":13.65}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think, given the contextualized and individualized nature of that inquiry, that's going to be difficult.","start":2461.18,"stop":2465.77,"duration":4.59},{"text":"But I think the record nevertheless answers your question because you can show a marked increase in diversity under the plan at issue.","start":2465.77,"stop":2472.25,"duration":6.48},{"text":"I just -- I've just explained to you how the record confirms that holistic admissions of African-Americans and Hispanics increased markedly in each year. If you look at student body diversity overall, African-American enrollment increased by two, doubled from 2002 to 2008 from about 3 percent to about 6 percent.","start":2472.25,"stop":2493.47,"duration":21.22}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- one of the things I find troubling about your argument is the suggestion that there is something deficient about the African-American students and the Hispanic students who are admitted under the Top 10 Percent Plan.","start":2493.47,"stop":2507.69,"duration":14.22},{"text":"They're not dynamic.","start":2507.69,"stop":2509.09,"duration":1.4},{"text":"They're not leaders.","start":2509.09,"stop":2510.43,"duration":1.34},{"text":"They're not change agents.","start":2510.43,"stop":2512.07,"duration":1.64},{"text":"And I don't know what the basis for that is.","start":2512.07,"stop":2514.605,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2514.605,"stop":2514.97,"duration":0.36}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- really it's based on a terrible stereotyping that --","start":2514.97,"stop":2519.21,"duration":4.24}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's --","start":2519.21,"stop":2520.6,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the basis for that --","start":2520.6,"stop":2521.81,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It's exactly the opposite.","start":2521.81,"stop":2523.84,"duration":2.03},{"text":"This Court has said time and again that you can't assume that minorities think alike just because they have the same skin color.","start":2523.84,"stop":2530.29,"duration":6.45},{"text":"What the University of Texas does is it considers -- it takes into account the fact that people who come from different experiences, different backgrounds are going to have different contributions to the class.","start":2530.29,"stop":2541.21,"duration":10.92},{"text":"If you had the situation where all the out-of-state admits or most of the out-of-state admits were coming predominantly from western States, then the University of Texas and any university would try to get out-of-state admits from other parts of the country because it would want the -- both perspectives.","start":2541.21,"stop":2555.55,"duration":14.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But -- maybe I misapprehended either the question or the answer.","start":2555.55,"stop":2559.865,"duration":4.31},{"text":"But you're the one that says race can be relevant.","start":2559.865,"stop":2563.385,"duration":3.52},{"text":"And then in answer to Justice Alito's question, you say, oh, that's stereotyping.","start":2563.385,"stop":2567.505,"duration":4.12},{"text":"It seems to me that you're inconsistent.","start":2567.505,"stop":2570.4,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2570.4,"stop":2570.57,"duration":0.17},{"text":"What stereotyping, Your Honor, is saying, that just because you get a sufficient number of blacks or Hispanics under the 10 percent plan means that you can't look at the class holistically and say, we're not getting a variety of perspectives among African-Americans or Hispanics.","start":2570.57,"stop":2584.945,"duration":14.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":2584.945,"stop":2585.13,"duration":0.18},{"text":"But what is the basis for saying that? That's what I don't understand.","start":2585.13,"stop":2588.08,"duration":2.95},{"text":"It's kind of the assumption that if the -- if a student -- if a black student or a Hispanic student is admitted as part of the Top 10 Percent Plan, it has to be because that student didn't have to compete against very many whites and -- and Asians.","start":2588.08,"stop":2601.77,"duration":13.69},{"text":"In -- in the high school class, it's a really pernicious stereotype.","start":2601.77,"stop":2605.395,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- it's not a stereotype at all, Your Honor.","start":2605.395,"stop":2607.36,"duration":1.97},{"text":"It's based on the undeniable fact about the manner in which the Top 10 Percent Plan operates.","start":2607.36,"stop":2613.385,"duration":6.03},{"text":"The Top 10 Percent Law was enacted in response to Hopwood, and there's nothing -- there's no challenge to the law in this case that admits many well-deserving students.","start":2613.385,"stop":2621.49,"duration":8.1},{"text":"But the fact is, is that -- that the way that the Top 10 Percent Law admits minority students is by admitting those students from the lower-performing, racially identifiable schools. And the way -- the reason we know that is because if you look at the Bill Analysis decided by Justice Ginsburg in her dissent the last time we were here, that analysis specifically says on page 4, because of the persistence of segregation in this State, minority students will be admitted under the Top 10 Percent Plan.","start":2621.49,"stop":2648.81,"duration":27.32}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't doubt that that is one of the things that it does, and I would have thought that that would be something that you would regard as beneficial.","start":2648.81,"stop":2657.63,"duration":8.82}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"We --","start":2657.63,"stop":2657.75,"duration":0.12}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Wasn't that the -- the reason for adopting affirmative action in the first place because there are people who have been severely disadvantaged through discrimination and -- and lack of wealth, and they should be given a benefit in admission --","start":2657.75,"stop":2672.18,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And the University --","start":2672.18,"stop":2673.09,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- but that's one -- one of the things that it does, but it's not the only thing that it does.","start":2673.09,"stop":2676.55,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the University of Texas applauds those students.","start":2676.55,"stop":2679.83,"duration":3.28},{"text":"It wants those students. Those students are admitted through holistic review as well.","start":2679.83,"stop":2683.895,"duration":4.07},{"text":"Nevertheless, the University can look at an incoming class and determine that not all the perspectives among a particular class of students is being represented.","start":2683.895,"stop":2692.6,"duration":8.7},{"text":"This is straight out of the Harvard plan in Bakke --","start":2692.6,"stop":2695.12,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a statistic that jumped out at me, which it seems to me contrary to the stereotype on which the Fifth Circuit panel proceeds and on which you proceed.","start":2695.12,"stop":2704.31,"duration":9.19},{"text":"Of the African-American and Hispanic students who were admitted under the Top 10 Percent Plan, 21 percent had parents who had either a bachelor's degree or a four-year degree.","start":2704.31,"stop":2719.31,"duration":15},{"text":"And for the holistic admittees, African-Americans and Hispanics, it's 26 percent.","start":2719.31,"stop":2725.725,"duration":6.41},{"text":"This is from a Class of 2008. So there isn't -- it seems to me it refutes the idea that all of these minority students who were admitted under -- or most of them admitted under the 10 percent plan come just from these predominantly overwhelmingly black and Hispanic schools with poor students.","start":2725.725,"stop":2746.77,"duration":21.05},{"text":"It's just -- it doesn't seem to be true.","start":2746.77,"stop":2748.43,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we've never claimed that all of them do.","start":2748.43,"stop":2750.4,"duration":1.97},{"text":"That's a straw man argument.","start":2750.4,"stop":2751.77,"duration":1.37},{"text":"But if you look at the data, what you would find, in particular look at the 2008 profile that we cited in our last brief on page 33, you do find that on balance, there is a difference in background of the students, African-American, Hispanic students, coming in through the holistic plan versus the Top 10 Percent Plan.","start":2751.77,"stop":2768.5,"duration":16.73},{"text":"And that's no surprise, given the obvious purpose of the Top 10 Percent Plan.","start":2768.5,"stop":2772.76,"duration":4.26},{"text":"The purpose of the holistic review plan is to take into account all considerations.","start":2772.76,"stop":2776.43,"duration":3.67}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"We know that -- can you -- can you say this? Let me read you two phrases from Fisher I.","start":2776.43,"stop":2780.83,"duration":4.4},{"text":"The first phrase says this: \"The decision to pursue\" -- and Fisher I, obviously, put together a Court of people who don't agree necessarily on affirmative action.","start":2780.83,"stop":2790.88,"duration":10.05},{"text":"Generally we agreed on those words. Words 1: \"The decision to pursue the educational benefits that flow from student diversity is, in substantial measure, an academic judgment to which some, but not complete, judicial deference is proper.\" Okay? Now, words No. 2: The University must provide a, quote, \"reasoned, principled explanation for the academic decision to pursue diversity.\" Your plan is pursuing diversity among the 25 percent who are not admitted under the Top 10 Plan. Your principled, reasoned explanation for that academic decision is?","start":2790.88,"stop":2848.675,"duration":57.8}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, it's set forth in the 2004 proposal which is in the Supplemental Joint Appendix.","start":2848.675,"stop":2853.72,"duration":5.04},{"text":"It's elaborated by the deposition testimony. Let me give you some -- a few pieces of that. Number one is, is the University made clear it was pursuing the educational benefits of diversity in the broad sense specifically recognized by this Court. This is on pages 1 through 3 of the Supplemental Joint Appendix. Number two, the University made clear that in its judgment the Top 10 Percent Plan, in particular as it grew to crowd out the class, was compromising its educational objectives.","start":2853.72,"stop":2880.52,"duration":26.8},{"text":"That's on page 25a and 31a of the Supplemental Joint Appendix. Number three, the University made clear that because of the decrease in student body diversity under the very race-neutral policies that our opponents are asking this Court to impose, that additional measures were necessary to make sure that it was achieving its educational objectives. All of that is laid out in far more detail, frankly, than it was in Grutter or that it was in the Harvard plan.","start":2880.52,"stop":2909.48,"duration":28.96},{"text":"It's amplified by the deposition testimony.","start":2909.48,"stop":2911.815,"duration":2.34},{"text":"In particular, look at the testimony of Ms. Ishop and Mr. Walker.","start":2911.815,"stop":2915.43,"duration":3.61},{"text":"And I can elaborate that --","start":2915.43,"stop":2916.645,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And --","start":2916.645,"stop":2916.9,"duration":0.26}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"-- on that, if you would like.","start":2916.9,"stop":2917.81,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And you're talking about the 2004 plan?","start":2917.81,"stop":2920.05,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2920.05,"stop":2920.77,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":2920.77,"stop":2921.42,"duration":0.65},{"text":"One of the things that it said is that you would review the plan every five years.","start":2921.42,"stop":2925.725,"duration":4.3},{"text":"Has that happened?","start":2925.725,"stop":2926.825,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It absolutely has.","start":2926.825,"stop":2928.275,"duration":1.45},{"text":"We -- in the record, Your Honor, it's established that we have reviewed it on an annual basis.","start":2928.275,"stop":2932.705,"duration":4.43},{"text":"We reviewed it on a five-year basis.","start":2932.705,"stop":2934.85,"duration":2.14},{"text":"I was personally involved in part of that.","start":2934.85,"stop":2936.58,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How did you measure -- how did you measure whether or not the plan was working --","start":2936.58,"stop":2939.86,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor --","start":2939.86,"stop":2940.4,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- under the review that you undertook?","start":2940.4,"stop":2942.4,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"We would look to a number of different --","start":2942.4,"stop":2944.08,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":2944.08,"stop":2944.16,"duration":0.08},{"text":"What did you -- what did you look to?","start":2944.16,"stop":2945.7,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and I'll answer that question.","start":2945.7,"stop":2947.61,"duration":1.91},{"text":"We looked -- we looked both to student body enrollment.","start":2947.61,"stop":2951.25,"duration":3.64},{"text":"We do look to classroom diversity.","start":2951.25,"stop":2954.48,"duration":3.23},{"text":"We look at feedback from students; from faculty -- after all, this is an academic judgment, as this Court said in the Fisher case, and certainly said in the Grutter and the Bakke case -- we look to -- to the racial climate, including incidents.","start":2954.48,"stop":2966.72,"duration":12.24},{"text":"There's briefs before you in the Black Students Association brief, Latino Organization briefs --","start":2966.72,"stop":2971.11,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":2971.11,"stop":2971.58,"duration":0.47},{"text":"It's -- it's an academic judgment, but the facts are not an academic judgment.","start":2971.58,"stop":2976.42,"duration":4.84}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- well --","start":2976.42,"stop":2977.34,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"To say that, you know, if the faculty thinks we're doing great, we must be doing great.","start":2977.34,"stop":2982.365,"duration":5.02},{"text":"I mean, the facts are the facts.","start":2982.365,"stop":2984,"duration":1.64},{"text":"I don't think we give the faculty a leg up on -- on what the facts are.","start":2984,"stop":2988.8,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And look at the facts, Your Honor.","start":2988.8,"stop":2990.05,"duration":1.25},{"text":"In 2002, you had 272 African-American enrollees out of a class of 8,000.","start":2990.05,"stop":2994.84,"duration":4.79},{"text":"Even Judge Garza recognized in note 11 of his decision that the University of Texas had not achieved its critical mass or educational benefits in 2004.","start":2994.84,"stop":3003.19,"duration":8.35},{"text":"So I don't think that that seriously is debatable.","start":3003.19,"stop":3005.64,"duration":2.45},{"text":"If it is, then we should have a remand and an opportunity to put in more evidence --","start":3005.64,"stop":3009.73,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you're talking about the time -- Grutter said that we did not expect these sorts of programs to be around in 25 years, and that was 12 -- 12 years ago.","start":3009.73,"stop":3020.07,"duration":10.34},{"text":"Are -- are we going to hit the deadline? Is this going to be done on -- in your view in 12 years?","start":3020.07,"stop":3025.4,"duration":5.33}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I'm not here to give you a date, but what I would say is this: There are systematic problems that these problems -- that these policies are attempting to address, including the test score gap between -- between African-Americans and Hispanics.","start":3025.4,"stop":3038.345,"duration":12.94},{"text":"And -- and the record in this case overwhelmingly shows that without the addition of race, student body diversity suffered, particularly among African-Americans.","start":3038.345,"stop":3047.58,"duration":9.24}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":3047.58,"stop":3048.18,"duration":0.6},{"text":"I don't know whether that's a yes or no.","start":3048.18,"stop":3049.98,"duration":1.8},{"text":"But it was important in the Grutter Court that these were a temporary -- as necessary, temporary expedience because we're talking about giving you the extraordinary power to consider race in making important decisions.","start":3049.98,"stop":3063.6,"duration":13.62},{"text":"And we don't do that as a matter of -- matter of --","start":3063.6,"stop":3064.93,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And we -- we appreciate the --","start":3064.93,"stop":3066.12,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- course. And so it was important in Grutter to say, look, this can't go on forever, 25 years.","start":3066.12,"stop":3071.535,"duration":5.41},{"text":"And when do you think your program will be done?","start":3071.535,"stop":3074.59,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, as soon as we -- we can achieve the same -- sufficient numbers for the educational benefits of diversity without taking race into account, we will no longer take race into account. The strict-scrutiny inquiry focuses on whether or not there are race-neutral alternatives, which I think really is the way to police this.","start":3074.59,"stop":3091.695,"duration":17.11},{"text":"And in this case, because it's backward-looking, you look to whether or not the University policies in place for seven years -- this is a distinct case.","start":3091.695,"stop":3099.42,"duration":7.72},{"text":"You have a record of seven years of trying the race-neutral alternatives that they're proposing, top 10 percent, plus race-blind holistic review.","start":3099.42,"stop":3106.58,"duration":7.16},{"text":"And the record tells you what happened.","start":3106.58,"stop":3107.975,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, how -- what percentage of the class is -- what legacy is that a consideration for?","start":3107.975,"stop":3114.26,"duration":6.29}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"University of Texas does not do legacy, Your Honor. But if you look at what happened -- and this is the second reason why it's necessary -- it's -- it's -- I don't think it's debatable that student body diversity suffered at the University of Texas under the policies that they're asking this Court to impose.","start":3114.26,"stop":3129.3,"duration":15.04},{"text":"And in particular under African-Americans where you had evidence of glaring racial isolation, certainly in the classroom where 90 percent of the classes, the most common size, are zero or one African-American --","start":3129.3,"stop":3139.76,"duration":10.46}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, on that subject, I don't know of any -- you haven't mentioned in your briefs anything that the University of Texas has done to increase racial diversity at the classroom level, other than this admissions program. And I mentioned during your -- your friend's argument a way in which you could determine whether the top 10 admittees are any more or less likely to enroll in classes -- small classes where there is a lack of racial diversity than the holistic admittees.","start":3139.76,"stop":3171.9,"duration":32.14},{"text":"And I don't see -- and you haven't made any effort, as far as I can tell, to measure that.","start":3171.9,"stop":3176.87,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me answer that in two ways. One, doubling the enrollment of African-American students, which happened from 2002 to 2008, is going to increase diversity in the classroom.","start":3176.87,"stop":3189.205,"duration":12.34},{"text":"And we've looked at that, and it has. Secondly, with respect to diversity among particular majors, University does take holistic consideration of where -- which schools students are admitted to as well.","start":3189.205,"stop":3200.68,"duration":11.47},{"text":"So its policy addresses that concern as well. But what the record does show, Your Honor, conclusively, I think, is that diversity languished at the University of Texas in the period where we had race-blind holistic admissions plus the top 10 percent, and that the plan at issue here was necessary to supplement that.","start":3200.68,"stop":3217.48,"duration":16.8},{"text":"The Texas legislature found that.","start":3217.48,"stop":3219.72,"duration":2.24}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But I don't -- you could have determined whether this is -- whether the admission -- the addition of race to the holistic equation has done anything to increase classroom diversity.","start":3219.72,"stop":3230.2,"duration":10.48}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"It has.","start":3230.2,"stop":3230.5,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And you haven't done that.","start":3230.5,"stop":3231.595,"duration":1.09}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we've looked at in the five-year analysis --","start":3231.595,"stop":3235.565,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3235.565,"stop":3235.76,"duration":0.2},{"text":"As -- as comparing, this goes back to your -- your underlying claim is there's something deficient about the top 10 admittees, and I -- maybe -- if you have -- do you have evidence that they are less likely to -- to enroll in the classes where there's a lack of classroom diversity --","start":3235.76,"stop":3250.43,"duration":14.67}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"There's a different breakdown there, Your Honor.","start":3250.43,"stop":3252.36,"duration":1.93},{"text":"But I think there's two dimensions to this diversity issue.","start":3252.36,"stop":3255.515,"duration":3.15},{"text":"One is just the glaring racial isolation that existed, particularly among African-Americans. And then two is an effort, through the addition of holistic review, to admit minorities from different viewpoints, experiences, and perspectives. That gets back right to the core of the essence of the diversity embraced by this Court in Bakke. If you look at the Harvard brief in the Bakke case, page 17, it specifically says, \"Our interests in the educational benefits of diversity would not be met if all of minority students were -- were coming from depressed socioeconomic backgrounds.\"","start":3255.515,"stop":3287.35,"duration":31.84}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- but that's where I'm looking for evidence that that's true.","start":3287.35,"stop":3290.85,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And I would --","start":3290.85,"stop":3291.26,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it -- what is it -- have you looked at the top 10 percent admittees, for example, to see how many of them are leaders, which is certainly -- and certainly a legitimate factor to look for, students who are leaders. At -- do you say, well, there are -- there are just not very many leaders here; these are students who all they do is study.","start":3291.26,"stop":3309,"duration":17.74},{"text":"There's no evidence of that as far as I can tell.","start":3309,"stop":3311.765,"duration":2.76}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think it's -- it's seriously debatable, but if we need evidence on this, let us put it into the record that a class selected by the holistic consideration of numerous factors is going to be more diverse in a way that promotes the University's educational interests than a class selected by a single factor. And let me give you the deposition --","start":3311.765,"stop":3328.91,"duration":17.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3328.91,"stop":3329.45,"duration":0.54},{"text":"That's not -- that's not the question.","start":3329.45,"stop":3331.29,"duration":1.84},{"text":"It's whether students selected under the holistic process without giving extra points because of race.","start":3331.29,"stop":3337.625,"duration":6.34}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And there's two problems with that.","start":3337.625,"stop":3339.535,"duration":1.91},{"text":"One, they're not -- minority students are not going to be selected.","start":3339.535,"stop":3342,"duration":2.47},{"text":"It's going to become, as the Fifth Circuit found, essentially an all-white enterprise.","start":3342,"stop":3346.22,"duration":4.22},{"text":"That's the first problem. And then the second --","start":3346.22,"stop":3348.09,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Wait.","start":3348.09,"stop":3348.3,"duration":0.21},{"text":"What are you telling me? The holistic process, if race is not expressly considered, will not result in any minority students?","start":3348.3,"stop":3356.12,"duration":7.82}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":3356.12,"stop":3356.75,"duration":0.63},{"text":"It's not zero, Your Honor. But take 2002 for example.","start":3356.75,"stop":3360.475,"duration":3.72},{"text":"272 African-Americans out of a class of 8,000.","start":3360.475,"stop":3364.36,"duration":3.89},{"text":"That's glaring racial isolation. University of Texas concluded that was unacceptable. And I don't think that that's seriously debatable. But again, if we need more evidence on why having 90 percent of our classrooms of the most common size was zero or one African-American doesn't achieve our educational objectives --","start":3364.36,"stop":3380.1,"duration":15.74}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What -- what unique -- what unique perspective does a minority student bring to a physics class?","start":3380.1,"stop":3385.765,"duration":5.66}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor --","start":3385.765,"stop":3387.08,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're counting those among the classes in which there are no minority students.","start":3387.08,"stop":3391.99,"duration":4.91},{"text":"And I'm just wondering what the benefits of diversity are in that situation?","start":3391.99,"stop":3395.535,"duration":3.55}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we can talk about different classes, but -- but this Court has -- has accepted in Bakke and Grutter, and I think it accepted again in Fisher I, that student body diversity is a compelling interest. Our friends do not ask this Court to rule -- overrule any aspect of Grutter or of Fisher or of Bakke --","start":3395.535,"stop":3413.01,"duration":17.48}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure we said it's class by class.","start":3413.01,"stop":3415.66,"duration":2.65}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"And we're not asking --","start":3415.66,"stop":3416.28,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure we said it's the case class by class.","start":3416.28,"stop":3418.79,"duration":2.51}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, that's a caricature of the University's interests here.","start":3418.79,"stop":3421.97,"duration":3.18},{"text":"We made clear in the 2004 proposal and throughout --","start":3421.97,"stop":3424.68,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a caricature of the argument you're making.","start":3424.68,"stop":3427.9,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Student body -- classroom diversity, Your Honor, if that's what you're focused on, was one aspect that the University looked to.","start":3427.9,"stop":3434.09,"duration":6.19},{"text":"I mean, the University is being hit by both sides here.","start":3434.09,"stop":3436.62,"duration":2.53},{"text":"Maybe that's fair because of the nature of strict scrutiny. But on the one hand, we're going to look to prove the way in which diversity was lacking with diversity.","start":3436.62,"stop":3444.5,"duration":7.88},{"text":"And then on the other hand, every time we point to something, our opponent seizes on it say, ah-ha, that's your objective. Our objective is the educational benefits of diversity in the very way that this Court has recognized for decades. Now, the other --","start":3444.5,"stop":3456.5,"duration":12}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"One of the --","start":3456.5,"stop":3457.41,"duration":0.91}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Kennedy, I didn't want to --","start":3457.41,"stop":3458.55,"duration":1.14}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I was going to ask: What evidence would you have put in if you had been successful in your motion to remand? And preliminary to that, I assume that district court would have had authority to remand to -- to allow the summary judgment record to be expanded or reopened?","start":3458.55,"stop":3476.4,"duration":17.85}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the court of appeals would have had authority in our view.","start":3476.4,"stop":3478.87,"duration":2.47},{"text":"The district court -- again, this case is on -- here on summary judgment.","start":3478.87,"stop":3482.715,"duration":3.85},{"text":"I mean, the first question is whether the --","start":3482.715,"stop":3484.06,"duration":1.34}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand --","start":3484.06,"stop":3484.36,"duration":0.3}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the triable issues at fact --","start":3484.36,"stop":3485.11,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":3485.11,"stop":3485.55,"duration":0.44},{"text":"But -- but I -- I -- but -- but why did you want a remand? Because you wanted to expand the summary judgment record? And if so, what additional evidence would you have put in?","start":3485.55,"stop":3493.45,"duration":7.9}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":3493.45,"stop":3493.85,"duration":0.4},{"text":"If there are any shortcomings that this Court sees, certainly what -- if they -- if you feel that there are deficiencies in looking on a more granular basis between the nature of the holistic admits that are admitted, the unique skills, qualities, talents that those admits bring as change agents and bridge builders, we can put that evidence in.","start":3493.85,"stop":3511.72,"duration":17.87},{"text":"We can put in additional evidence.","start":3511.72,"stop":3513.11,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But you -- but you asked for the remand --","start":3513.11,"stop":3514.96,"duration":1.85}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3514.96,"stop":3515.07,"duration":0.11}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and my question was: What evidence did you propose to put in if your motion had been granted?","start":3515.07,"stop":3521.485,"duration":6.41}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, we didn't -- we -- we -- we specifically pointed to evidence on standing, and we talked about that, if the Court would like to supplement the evidence in other respects.","start":3521.485,"stop":3529.85,"duration":8.36},{"text":"And I -- and I think, frankly, we would be entitled to a remand. If you look at the Grutter case, for example, this Court rejected the argument that the percentage plan was an adequate substitute for the holistic consideration of race.","start":3529.85,"stop":3541,"duration":11.15},{"text":"It didn't require evidentiary findings on that.","start":3541,"stop":3543.195,"duration":2.2},{"text":"But if the Court thinks these findings are necessary, then the University of Texas can put in -- certainly put in additional evidence in the record showing why these holistic students, selected across the broad diversity recognized by Bakke, contribute meaningfully to the class in this issue.","start":3543.195,"stop":3559.425,"duration":16.23}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know what that --","start":3559.425,"stop":3560.1,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me --","start":3560.1,"stop":3560.31,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know what that proves.","start":3560.31,"stop":3561.78,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Sure.","start":3561.78,"stop":3562.435,"duration":0.65},{"text":"I -- I'm sure that there are holistic admittees who were great students.","start":3562.435,"stop":3566.48,"duration":4.05},{"text":"They made a wonderful contribution to the university. I'll -- I don't know whether you're going to be able to determine that they would have not -- they would not have been admitted if race hadn't been taken into account.","start":3566.48,"stop":3575.61,"duration":9.13},{"text":"They probably -- they would have -- many of them would have been.","start":3575.61,"stop":3578.51,"duration":2.9},{"text":"Maybe all of them.","start":3578.51,"stop":3579.925,"duration":1.41},{"text":"But beyond that, what is to say that there are not comparable students who were among the top 10 percent admittees? I bet there are.","start":3579.925,"stop":3588.505,"duration":8.58}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I think certainly you can conclude, Your Honor, that, where you have all out-of-state students, all students from the best schools in Texas that don't rank, students who fall just below that 10 percent but nevertheless are great students, if we're not getting adequate diversity out of the -- that class, special class of students, we're not meeting our educational objectives. If you have -- if you have doubts about whether or not the record --","start":3588.505,"stop":3610.47,"duration":21.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Garre, this is the fundamental problem that I think Justice Alito is pointing to, and you're sort of talking past each other. So maybe I'll explain his view. (Laughter.)","start":3610.47,"stop":3625.26,"duration":14.79}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Strange, isn't that?","start":3625.26,"stop":3626.42,"duration":1.16}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I could use -- I can use the help. (Laughter.)","start":3626.42,"stop":3628.25,"duration":1.83}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I'll explain what his view is. He seems to think that you didn't study the 10 percent admittees enough before -- to make -- to see whether that group was diverse in and of itself, whether you had enough people within that group that were change agents, that were -- had -- were not just poor people, but people with college-educated parents, whatever other diverse view factors.","start":3628.25,"stop":3661.37,"duration":33.12},{"text":"He's -- I think he's saying, you didn't look to see if the 10 percent plan did enough for you.","start":3661.37,"stop":3668.68,"duration":7.31}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3668.68,"stop":3669.24,"duration":0.56}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And with deficits that plan created, that you should have filled in the holistic-looking.","start":3669.24,"stop":3677.925,"duration":8.69},{"text":"So he thinks it's fatally flawed.","start":3677.925,"stop":3680.965,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":3680.965,"stop":3681.48,"duration":0.51}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right? Because of that.","start":3681.48,"stop":3683.07,"duration":1.59},{"text":"So that's his view, I think. So assuming that view, what's your answer?","start":3683.07,"stop":3687.18,"duration":4.11}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well -- well, that's my question.","start":3687.18,"stop":3688.62,"duration":1.44},{"text":"But -- (Laughter.)","start":3688.62,"stop":3689.06,"duration":0.44}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let me -- let me answer that question.","start":3689.06,"stop":3691.27,"duration":2.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I know.","start":3691.27,"stop":3691.51,"duration":0.24},{"text":"He said it wasn't, right?","start":3691.51,"stop":3692.7,"duration":1.19}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"First, we did look at that.","start":3692.7,"stop":3695.215,"duration":2.52},{"text":"We had seven years of experience under the race-blind holistic admissions policy.","start":3695.215,"stop":3699.21,"duration":3.99},{"text":"And what the university found -- this is at page 31 and 25a of the Supplemental Joint Appendix --","start":3699.21,"stop":3705.1,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That was with the ten -- so seven years --","start":3705.1,"stop":3707.35,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Race-blind --","start":3707.35,"stop":3708.56,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Race-blind --","start":3708.56,"stop":3709.34,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"-- race-blind holistic, and up to 10 --","start":3709.34,"stop":3710.55,"duration":1.21}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- and a certain number of them were with the 10 percent --","start":3710.55,"stop":3712.84,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Absolutely.","start":3712.84,"stop":3713.46,"duration":0.62},{"text":"And what we found was that, particularly as the Top 10 Percent Plan began to grow and crowd out more of the admissions pool, the university was not meeting its educational objectives. That -- that's what it found specifically.","start":3713.46,"stop":3726.68,"duration":13.22},{"text":"It stated that on page 31a of the Supplemental Joint Appendix. We also knew -- and it's interesting: The Texas legislature found that the holistic plan was a necessary complement.","start":3726.68,"stop":3737.34,"duration":10.66},{"text":"The Texas district court judge did.","start":3737.34,"stop":3739.695,"duration":2.36},{"text":"The Texas court of appeals judge and his colleague did.","start":3739.695,"stop":3742.535,"duration":2.84},{"text":"And all -- what all of them recognized is the obvious way in which the Top 10 Percent Plan operates with respect to --","start":3742.535,"stop":3749.34,"duration":6.81}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And if you did not have --","start":3749.34,"stop":3750.44,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right.","start":3750.44,"stop":3750.95,"duration":0.51},{"text":"But there's --","start":3750.95,"stop":3751.88,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if you did not have the Top 10 Percent Plan, but you did have the program that you're advocating for here, the holistic review, would you have a better or worse chance of achieving the diversity you seek?","start":3751.88,"stop":3765.175,"duration":13.3}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I -- I think the first thing I would like to say is that it's a different way.","start":3765.175,"stop":3769.32,"duration":4.14},{"text":"And I don't mean to dodge the question by that. But what I would say is, if -- if that's a meaningful difference, then this plan is -- is in an even stronger light than the plan in Bakke and the Harvard plan.","start":3769.32,"stop":3779.94,"duration":10.62},{"text":"Because the University of Texas has heeded this Court's message.","start":3779.94,"stop":3782.995,"duration":3.05},{"text":"It's taken three-quarters of the class that it selects through a facially race-neutral system, the Top 10 Percent Law.","start":3782.995,"stop":3790.04,"duration":7.05},{"text":"And what we're here debating is whether or not it can complement that policy by taking race into account for a quarter. Now, it may actually be that the university could achieve more diversity through the pure Grutter-Bakke-style plan, but we think, working with the Texas legislature, we've come up with a hydrid -- hybrid plan that works together to both -- to both address this Court's concerns about using race too much in the process, and addressing University of Texas's legitimate, core academic concerns about compiling a class that's diverse in all the ways that are appreciated by Bakke. If I could read one aspect of the deposition testimony here.","start":3790.04,"stop":3829.735,"duration":39.7},{"text":"This is from Ms. Ishop on page 253a of the Joint Appendix, and she explains why top 10 percent alone is not sufficient. What she says is, quote, \"Considering an applicant on the basis of just their test score and class rank leaves out all of that life experience and circumstantial experience that an applicant faces that's","start":3829.735,"stop":3847.66,"duration":17.92},{"text":"also important not -- not only to how they developed and the type of student they are, but also to what they contribute to our campus.\" That's what the holistic policy adds. If you exclude race from that mix, you not only aren't looking at the individual in all its respects -- and race still does matter in Austin and across this country -- but you're -- you're preventing the University from rounding out its class from complementing the single-minded way that the Top 10 Percent Law to achieve its diversity objectives in a way that is narrowly tailored to its interests, which this Court has found compelling.","start":3847.66,"stop":3883.36,"duration":35.7}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, all of the colloquy so far indicates to me that, if you had a remand, you would not have put in much different or much more evidence than we have in the record right now.","start":3883.36,"stop":3895.17,"duration":11.81},{"text":"Is that --","start":3895.17,"stop":3895.4,"duration":0.23}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":3895.4,"stop":3895.555,"duration":0.15}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"-- is that correct?","start":3895.555,"stop":3896.665,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not, Your Honor.","start":3896.665,"stop":3897.97,"duration":1.3},{"text":"I mean, look, we think that the record is sufficient.","start":3897.97,"stop":3899.85,"duration":1.88},{"text":"We think that the Fifth Circuit got it right. But -- but to be clear, we can certainly put in plenty of additional evidence.","start":3899.85,"stop":3905.48,"duration":5.63},{"text":"I mean, there was a trial in Grutter, as Your Honor pointed out in your decision in Fisher I.","start":3905.48,"stop":3909.5,"duration":4.02},{"text":"There's been no trial here. There is, at a minimum -- if -- if -- if our evidence doesn't cross the bar on strict scrutiny, at a minimum, we put in triable issues of fact on whether or not the holistic plan was a necessary offset, whether or not the university was achieving its educational objectives in an environment in which you had 272 African-American students enroll out of an incoming class of 8,000, an environment in which 90 percent of the classrooms had -- the most common side had zero to one.","start":3909.5,"stop":3936.5,"duration":27}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But why can't we make those inferences from the record? I mean, if -- if you had a trial, you'd have credibility.","start":3936.5,"stop":3941.97,"duration":5.47},{"text":"You'd have experts and so forth --","start":3941.97,"stop":3943.28,"duration":1.31}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I -- I think you can make those going in the University's favor.","start":3943.28,"stop":3946.89,"duration":3.61},{"text":"And one aspect of that, frankly, is the two-court rule that this Court usually applies.","start":3946.89,"stop":3950.72,"duration":3.83},{"text":"Both the district court and the court of appeals looked at this and made findings --","start":3950.72,"stop":3953.825,"duration":3.11}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"What you're saying, we -- we have a -- a remand only if we lose.","start":3953.825,"stop":3957.79,"duration":3.97},{"text":"I mean, that's what you're saying. (Laughter.)","start":3957.79,"stop":3959.14,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, I don't want to be result-oriented about this, Your Honor.","start":3959.14,"stop":3961.94,"duration":2.8},{"text":"But -- but I do think that -- that it's one thing to say in this record there are no triable facts, where the -- the courts below have gone that way.","start":3961.94,"stop":3969.47,"duration":7.53},{"text":"It's another thing to second-guess.","start":3969.47,"stop":3971.02,"duration":1.55},{"text":"And -- and the Court can.","start":3971.02,"stop":3971.82,"duration":0.8},{"text":"It's a summary judgment issue.","start":3971.82,"stop":3973,"duration":1.18},{"text":"But it's another thing, I think, to overstep the conclusions of the district court and the court of appeals here. And -- and I think it's particularly relevant here when it comes to the operation of the Top 10 Percent Law.","start":3973,"stop":3982.375,"duration":9.38},{"text":"Our friends have challenged the fact that the Fifth Circuit discussed the way in which it operated, saying that that's outside the record.","start":3982.375,"stop":3990.03,"duration":7.66},{"text":"If it is, let us put all that evidence directly into the record.","start":3990.03,"stop":3993.105,"duration":3.07},{"text":"But they've never disputed the way in which the Top 10 Percent Law operates. What -- what I'd like to say too is, if this Court rules that University of Texas can't consider race, or if it rules that universities that consider race have to die a death of a thousand cuts for doing so, we know exactly what's going to happen.","start":3993.105,"stop":4010.79,"duration":17.68},{"text":"Experience tells us that. University -- this happened at the University of Texas after the Hopwood case: Diversity plummeted, especially among African-Americans. Diversity plummeted at selective institutions in California, Berkeley, and UCLA, after Prop 209.","start":4010.79,"stop":4026.25,"duration":15.46},{"text":"And that is exactly what's taking place today at the University of Michigan. Now is not the time, and this is certainly not the case --","start":4026.25,"stop":4034.03,"duration":7.78}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"There are -- there are those who contend that it does not benefit African-Americans to -- to get them into the University of Texas where they do not do well, as opposed to having them go to a less-advanced school, a less -- a slower-track school where they do well.","start":4034.03,"stop":4054.925,"duration":20.89},{"text":"One of -- one of the briefs pointed out that -- that most of the -- most of the black scientists in this country don't come from schools like the University of Texas.","start":4054.925,"stop":4066.69,"duration":11.76}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"So this Court --","start":4066.69,"stop":4067.39,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They come from lesser schools where they do not feel that they're -- that they're being pushed ahead in -- in classes that are too -- too fast for them.","start":4067.39,"stop":4076.12,"duration":8.73}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court --","start":4076.12,"stop":4077.34,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm just not impressed by the fact that -- that the University of Texas may have fewer.","start":4077.34,"stop":4081.79,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Maybe it ought to have fewer.","start":4081.79,"stop":4083.45,"duration":1.66},{"text":"And maybe some -- you know, when you take more, the number of blacks, really competent blacks admitted to lesser schools, turns out to be less.","start":4083.45,"stop":4093.415,"duration":9.97},{"text":"And -- and I -- I don't think it -- it -- it stands to reason that it's a good thing for the University of Texas to admit as many blacks as possible.","start":4093.415,"stop":4102.845,"duration":9.43},{"text":"I just don't think --","start":4102.845,"stop":4103.64,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Gregory G. Garre","textObjs":[{"text":"This Court heard and rejected that argument, with respect, Justice Scalia, in the Grutter case, a case that our opponents haven't asked this Court to overrule.","start":4103.64,"stop":4111,"duration":7.36},{"text":"If you look at the academic performance of holistic minority admits versus the top 10 percent admits, over time, they -- they fare better. And, frankly, I don't think the solution to the problems with student body diversity can be to set up a system in which not only are minorities going to separate schools, they're going to inferior schools.","start":4111,"stop":4129.89,"duration":18.89},{"text":"I think what experience shows, at Texas, California, and Michigan, is that now is not the time and this is not the case to roll back student body diversity in America. Thank you, Your Honors.","start":4129.89,"stop":4139.635,"duration":9.74}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Counsel. General Verrilli.","start":4139.635,"stop":4160.975,"duration":21.34}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court: I'd like to make a point about the compelling-interest inquiry in light of what this Court said previously in Fisher, and then I'd like to make a point about the process aspect of the narrow-tailoring inquiry in light of what this Court said in Fisher, which I believe, Justice Kennedy, will address your concerns about whether race is determinative here.","start":4160.975,"stop":4180.165,"duration":19.19},{"text":"And then I'd like to move on to what I think this case comes down to, which is whether the University has made a sufficient showing of need to consider race in -- in its process. But before I make any of those points, Mr. Chief Justice, I -- I can provide some specific detail in response to the question you asked earlier related to the Parents Involved point. Here are the numbers.","start":4180.165,"stop":4200.07,"duration":19.9},{"text":"With respect to African-American students admitted through the holistic part of the program, in 2004, which was the last year before race was expressly considered, that number was 141 admitted through that number.","start":4200.07,"stop":4214.78,"duration":14.71},{"text":"And that was the high-water mark, really, of the period of -- of holistic review without race.","start":4214.78,"stop":4219.25,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In addition to the -- this is in addition to the 10 percent?","start":4219.25,"stop":4222.12,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":4222.12,"stop":4222.48,"duration":0.36},{"text":"This is just the holistic numbers. That number then moves up to 176 the following year, to 220 the year after, and to 262 in 2007.","start":4222.48,"stop":4233.275,"duration":10.8},{"text":"So the number of holistic admissions almost doubles, and that results in --","start":4233.275,"stop":4237.71,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But the problem, I guess, which is one issue that we haven't looked at is how do you tell how many of those --","start":4237.71,"stop":4242.8,"duration":5.09}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":4242.8,"stop":4242.96,"duration":0.16}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- would have been admitted if their race were not --","start":4242.96,"stop":4245.325,"duration":2.36}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You're right -- you're right that you can't tell for sure, but you do have a pretty good benchmark, I think, given that you have a number of years without considering race where 141 was the high-water mark.","start":4245.325,"stop":4255.16,"duration":9.84},{"text":"And so I do --","start":4255.16,"stop":4255.96,"duration":0.8}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wait a minute.","start":4255.96,"stop":4256.52,"duration":0.56},{"text":"The next two years you recited it was going up, even when race was considered.","start":4256.52,"stop":4261.33,"duration":4.81}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":4261.33,"stop":4261.66,"duration":0.33}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"So you could have said there -- there is a fluctuation before then, when race wasn't considered.","start":4261.66,"stop":4268.38,"duration":6.72},{"text":"That might have gone up, too.","start":4268.38,"stop":4269.3,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it went -- before they started considering race, it went up and down, frankly.","start":4269.3,"stop":4272.74,"duration":3.44},{"text":"But 141 was the high-water mark.","start":4272.74,"stop":4274.42,"duration":1.68},{"text":"There wasn't a consistent trajectory in those numbers.","start":4274.42,"stop":4276.85,"duration":2.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's an aspect of the holistic review process done at the University of Texas which may militate against the admission of African-American and Hispanic students for a -- an ostensibly race-neutral reason, and that is, that as I understand it, standardized test scores count pretty heavily in that process. One of the things the University says it's looking for is students with high SAT scores who are not in the top 10 percent of their class.","start":4276.85,"stop":4307.295,"duration":30.44},{"text":"And there are many who think that SAT scores and ACT scores are culturally biased.","start":4307.295,"stop":4313.235,"duration":5.94},{"text":"So if you put less emphasis on that, you might not have the numbers that you just recited. Well, it's rather strange that we -- we construct a process that may disadvantage African-American and Hispanic students for an ostensibly race-neutral reason.","start":4313.235,"stop":4329.57,"duration":16.34},{"text":"So then we have to add race in as a special factor to counteract that.","start":4329.57,"stop":4334.055,"duration":4.49}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It's -- or I guess what I'd say about that, Your Honor, is that in Grutter, what the Court specifically held was that the University is allowed to make those kinds of judgments in seeking to advance multiple objectives to maintain an academic environment of excellence, and to diversify the student body, both.","start":4334.055,"stop":4351.07,"duration":17.01}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the -- I thought the record showed the Top Ten admittees have a higher grade point average than the holistic African-American and Hispanic admittees.","start":4351.07,"stop":4359.96,"duration":8.89}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the -- the SAT scores are about the same.","start":4359.96,"stop":4362.01,"duration":2.05},{"text":"I'm not sure --","start":4362.01,"stop":4362.5,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But, I mean, once they get to --","start":4362.5,"stop":4363.76,"duration":1.26}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But I guess --","start":4363.76,"stop":4364.19,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Once they get to -- the SAT is supposed to predict how you are going to do in college.","start":4364.19,"stop":4367.5,"duration":3.31},{"text":"And I thought the record showed that the students who had lower SAT scores but did better as a -- by measure by high school rank did better at the University of Texas; isn't that -- isn't that the case?","start":4367.5,"stop":4379.47,"duration":11.97}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So I -- I'm not sure what the answer to that is, Your Honor, but this all goes to the compelling-interest inquiry, and let me focus on that. What the -- what the Court said last time around is to satisfy the compelling-interest inquiry, the University has got to articulate a reasoned, principled explanation for its decision to consider the educational benefits of diversity in a matter that this Court has found to be constitutional and substantial. The University of Texas has met that standard, has articulated exactly the same educational benefits of diversity at exactly the same level of specificity that this Court held constituted a compelling interest in the Grutter case at page 330. It's exactly the same. And the -- the principal argument that my friend Mr. Rein makes in challenging that is, well, actually a lot of that is post hoc rationalization, in particular, the effort to find whether you call it qualitative diversity, diversity within diversity is all post hoc rationalization, that is simply not so. If you look at page 1 of the Supplemental Joint Appendix, the first page of the 2004 Proposal, the University specifically says that what it's trying to accomplish is to create a diversity of perspectives among minority students.","start":4379.47,"stop":4449.96,"duration":70.49},{"text":"It says it again at page 28 in that proposal.","start":4449.96,"stop":4452.735,"duration":2.77},{"text":"The Director of Admissions Declaration, page 43 of the Joint Appendix, says it -- it says it throughout.","start":4452.735,"stop":4457.55,"duration":4.82},{"text":"So that there's no -- there's just no argument that it's a post hoc rationalization.","start":4457.55,"stop":4460.82,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Verrilli, do you -- you think all of this won't be necessary in another 13 years --","start":4460.82,"stop":4465.49,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":4465.49,"stop":4465.7,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"-- where we stop disadvantaging some applicants because of their race.","start":4465.7,"stop":4469.01,"duration":3.31}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What I think about that is that the -- the Court, I think, made a prediction in -- in Grutter that that would hopefully be the case.","start":4469.01,"stop":4475.4,"duration":6.39}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's a -- that's too short term.","start":4475.4,"stop":4477.52,"duration":2.12},{"text":"What do you think --","start":4477.52,"stop":4478.24,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think --","start":4478.24,"stop":4478.59,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"-- 30 years?","start":4478.59,"stop":4478.81,"duration":0.22}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the University's always --","start":4478.81,"stop":4480.17,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"What is it about this program that is going to change things, so that -- so that we can stop classifying people by race?","start":4480.17,"stop":4487.57,"duration":7.4}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":4487.57,"stop":4487.73,"duration":0.16},{"text":"I -- I -- I think the universities do make progress on this, and I think you do get to a point where you create a virtuous cycle. And -- and I think it does work, and I think that there's -- there's -- and -- and I think there's ample reason to -- to believe that it does work.","start":4487.73,"stop":4499.7,"duration":11.97},{"text":"And I think the key point here with respect to compelling interests is that this really is -- in -- in terms of having the educational benefits diversity, that's in the heartland of what the Court has said, is the area in which the University's expertise and experience deserves deference. Now, if I could go to the process point, with respect to --","start":4499.7,"stop":4517.145,"duration":17.45}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Just before, you -- you said -- I agreed with you, of course, that is what the Court said, the reasoned explanation.","start":4517.145,"stop":4524.22,"duration":7.07},{"text":"And it also said that this is a matter to which this Court will give some, but not complete, deference to what the University decides.","start":4524.22,"stop":4533.4,"duration":9.18},{"text":"What you're talking about is the need for the program. In addition to that -- and this is what I'd like you to focus on, because there could be a question of whether to send it back for more evidence or not.","start":4533.4,"stop":4545.345,"duration":11.95},{"text":"So in looking through the record so far, on this specific point, I found an affidavit by a person named Walker, and that person named Walker described seven years of efforts to measure this stuff; described meetings of the faculties; described all kinds of discussions; described conclusions of the faculty members, and the admissions officers, and others, that you did need -- you did need affirmative action in the 25 percent of the not -- of -- of the holistic part. Now, given that that's there, and I found nothing to the contrary, is there a need for another -- I mean, this is a loaded question, but I am curious. If you say \"yes,\" because -- I mean, you know, there may be something that you should put in as well.","start":4545.345,"stop":4595.285,"duration":49.94},{"text":"You may think it would help to put something in.","start":4595.285,"stop":4597.87,"duration":2.59},{"text":"You may think it's not necessary.","start":4597.87,"stop":4599.755,"duration":1.89},{"text":"But just to be safe, what do you think?","start":4599.755,"stop":4602.45,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah --","start":4602.45,"stop":4602.64,"duration":0.19}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that affidavit the relevant one? Are there others?","start":4602.64,"stop":4605.175,"duration":2.53}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah.","start":4605.175,"stop":4605.36,"duration":0.18},{"text":"I think -- I believe that's the affidavit from the director of admissions.","start":4605.36,"stop":4608.16,"duration":2.8},{"text":"And it is highly relevant, and there is other information.","start":4608.16,"stop":4610.54,"duration":2.38},{"text":"In the latter part of our brief, we documented it. We think -- you know, our view, we argued for affirmance.","start":4610.54,"stop":4615.59,"duration":5.05},{"text":"We think it's sufficient.","start":4615.59,"stop":4616.57,"duration":0.98},{"text":"But if there is doubt, I do think the additional kind of information that might be developed in this case would be to look at the kinds of questions that the Chief Justice was actually asking about, how did the -- how has the program worked in practice over the period of time in which it's been implemented.","start":4616.57,"stop":4634.33,"duration":17.76},{"text":"And I think that would be additional relevant information that might help make the judgment. If I could go to the process point, and then I will return to the need point. Process -- what the Court said last time around in this case was that the Court had to ensure itself without deference that the process provided for individualized consideration and that race did not predominate. Again, the University of Texas' plan has every one of what the Court in Grutter at page 334 said were the hallmarks of a narrowly tailored plan.","start":4634.33,"stop":4664.14,"duration":29.81},{"text":"No quota.","start":4664.14,"stop":4665.02,"duration":0.88},{"text":"Everybody competes against everybody else.","start":4665.02,"stop":4666.78,"duration":1.76},{"text":"No automatic award of points.","start":4666.78,"stop":4668.605,"duration":1.82},{"text":"Modest factor. And in addition -- and this goes to your question, Justice Kennedy, about whether there is an argument here that race is determinative -- Texas is different from the University of Michigan's law school plan in every one of the four ways that Your Honor identified as -- as being potentially troublesome and making race determinative. Unlike in Michigan, in Texas the percentage of African-American and Hispanics admitted does not mirror the percentage who applied.","start":4668.605,"stop":4694.34,"duration":25.74},{"text":"It's different. Unlike Texas, the number -- excuse me. Unlike Michigan, the number in Texas of -- of admissions fluctuates year over year.","start":4694.34,"stop":4702.89,"duration":8.55},{"text":"It's not the same every year. Unlike in Michigan, the bulk of Hispanic and African-American students admitted don't come from a small subset of the pool that's admitted after most are admitted based on grades. And unlike in Michigan, the -- there -- the admissions officers don't monitor the process all the way along, which would, as Your Honor suggested, perhaps create the risk that race would become determinative in latter stages of admissions.","start":4702.89,"stop":4729.22,"duration":26.33},{"text":"None of that is true here. So -- so I think with respect to --","start":4729.22,"stop":4731.89,"duration":2.67}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If none of that is true, how does the University know when it has achieved its objective?","start":4731.89,"stop":4736.18,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So --","start":4736.18,"stop":4736.705,"duration":0.52}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"At what point does it say, okay, the plan has worked?","start":4736.705,"stop":4739.9,"duration":3.19}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So I think -- I was trying to address process, and I -- and I'll go right now to need, which I think is -- is -- I really do think that you're right, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":4739.9,"stop":4746.99,"duration":7.09},{"text":"That's what the case comes down to. And I will answer your question directly, but I first want to make a point about how you don't -- how you shouldn't do it.","start":4746.99,"stop":4755.24,"duration":8.25},{"text":"And you shouldn't do it the way the Petitioner has suggested you should do it. What the Petitioner has said is that the -- in order to -- in order to assess need, and the -- and the only way to meet -- meet the need portion of the strict-scrutiny analysis, is for the University to set a, quote, \"demographic goal.\" That's the Petitioner's language.","start":4755.24,"stop":4775.21,"duration":19.97},{"text":"And then test whether or not they've made that goal.","start":4775.21,"stop":4777.89,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":4777.89,"stop":4778.13,"duration":0.24},{"text":"So how --","start":4778.13,"stop":4778.6,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And so --","start":4778.6,"stop":4778.99,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- how should they do it?","start":4778.99,"stop":4779.995,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So the -- the -- and the reason, of course, that that's no good is that that's just a Catch-22.","start":4779.995,"stop":4783.85,"duration":3.86}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":4783.85,"stop":4783.97,"duration":0.12},{"text":"I understand you disagree with their proposal.","start":4783.97,"stop":4785.93,"duration":1.96}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So -- so here's how you should do it, and we've -- we've laid it out in our brief: We think that the approach -- we think that approach is always going to be fatal in fact because, if they don't -- they -- they fail strict scrutiny if they --","start":4785.93,"stop":4797.14,"duration":11.21}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I know you don't agree with their approach. (Laughter.)","start":4797.14,"stop":4799.05,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I promise you I'm going to answer it.","start":4799.05,"stop":4800.73,"duration":1.68},{"text":"I just think these points are important. Then -- and so the -- with respect, we think our approach is faithful to Fisher because it's not always fatal in fact.","start":4800.73,"stop":4810.97,"duration":10.24},{"text":"What we say is that it's not an -- a critical mass, numerical kind of analysis.","start":4810.97,"stop":4817.55,"duration":6.58},{"text":"We say that what you do is you start with the University's articulation of the educational benefits it's trying to achieve.","start":4817.55,"stop":4825.8,"duration":8.25},{"text":"You require the University to state in concrete terms what success will look like.","start":4825.8,"stop":4832.51,"duration":6.71},{"text":"You then evaluate the evidence and analysis that the University relied on in order to make the judgment that it isn't where it needs to be and there -- and needs to consider race --","start":4832.51,"stop":4842.95,"duration":10.44}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm trying to get at the --","start":4842.95,"stop":4843.76,"duration":0.81}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4843.76,"stop":4843.85,"duration":0.09},{"text":"And so in the kinds of --","start":4843.85,"stop":4844.8,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- at a -- at a more concrete -- and so to look at what they say they want and see if they've done it, but how do you see it?","start":4844.8,"stop":4848.8,"duration":4}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And -- and you -- and so the kind -- you would look for concrete evidence.","start":4848.8,"stop":4851.635,"duration":2.84},{"text":"You know, well -- well-done classroom studies. Well-designed surveys of student attitudes and faculty attitudes.","start":4851.635,"stop":4858.18,"duration":6.55},{"text":"Graduation and retention rates.","start":4858.18,"stop":4860.46,"duration":2.28},{"text":"Are racial incidents going up and down -- up or down on -- on campus in frequency? You -- you know, there could be a whole list of them.","start":4860.46,"stop":4867.66,"duration":7.2},{"text":"But you would look at those.","start":4867.66,"stop":4868.97,"duration":1.31},{"text":"You would look at -- you would look at those.","start":4868.97,"stop":4871.6,"duration":2.63},{"text":"You would look at the University's analysis of those, and then you'd make a judgment whether the University has substantiated its case. And the burden, of course, is on the University.","start":4871.6,"stop":4879.165,"duration":7.56},{"text":"They've got to come in and convince you that they've substantiated their case that they need to consider race --","start":4879.165,"stop":4884.26,"duration":5.1}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And they -- they can do that with evidence that -- and -- and of events that occurred after the suit was brought?","start":4884.26,"stop":4891.715,"duration":7.45}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I think what --","start":4891.715,"stop":4893.3,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I'm not quite sure how that works.","start":4893.3,"stop":4894.84,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":4894.84,"stop":4895.03,"duration":0.19},{"text":"I think that they can -- and -- and as happened in Grutter, I think they have -- the -- the interests that they rely on have to be the interests that they contemporaneously identified when they adopted the program.","start":4895.03,"stop":4906.985,"duration":11.95},{"text":"I don't think there's an issue here on that. But I think the evidence can include evidence of how things are working in practice.","start":4906.985,"stop":4913.65,"duration":6.66},{"text":"For example, if they adopt a system and it does result in improvement, that does seem highly relevant and -- and consistent with what the Court held in Grutter was appropriate evidence.","start":4913.65,"stop":4922.295,"duration":8.65}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The reason I -- I think it's a matter of concern is -- what I heard from Mr. Garre were a lot of numbers.","start":4922.295,"stop":4928.095,"duration":5.8},{"text":"He said, look, this is why it's needed, and -- and, you know, we will know we're doing better when the numbers look better. And I just wonder whether the idea of surveys -- I looked at one of these surveys -- I don't remember this record or the -- the prior one -- and I have to say it was kind of sophomoric.","start":4928.095,"stop":4944.64,"duration":16.55},{"text":"I mean, do you feel that you've had enough interactions --","start":4944.64,"stop":4946.92,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4946.92,"stop":4947.06,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"-- with -- I mean, that was -- this is consideration of race.","start":4947.06,"stop":4950.06,"duration":3},{"text":"It's a very serious matter.","start":4950.06,"stop":4951.17,"duration":1.11}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":4951.17,"stop":4951.27,"duration":0.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And to pass out some survey and see, I don't think is an adequate --","start":4951.27,"stop":4955.37,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It certainly wouldn't be adequate by itself.","start":4955.37,"stop":4957.725,"duration":2.36},{"text":"It might be probative evidence in combination with other probative evidence.","start":4957.725,"stop":4961.17,"duration":3.44},{"text":"But -- you know, but the -- the question of classroom composition is hard evidence. And at some level, demographics are hard evidence too, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":4961.17,"stop":4968.13,"duration":6.96},{"text":"When you're talking about the African-American population at the University of Texas in -- in Austin, you're talking about a population of 3 or 400 kids in a class of 6,000, I think the -- the idea that there is a material risk of racial isolation in that situation is quite strong.","start":4968.13,"stop":4985.93,"duration":17.8},{"text":"The idea that there is a material chance that lots and lots of students are going to go --","start":4985.93,"stop":4990.43,"duration":4.5}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"600 is going to make the difference?","start":4990.43,"stop":4991.99,"duration":1.56}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It -- it -- it --","start":4991.99,"stop":4992.52,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It might well --","start":4992.52,"stop":4992.9,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"They wouldn't feel isolated with 600?","start":4992.9,"stop":4994.93,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"It might well make a significant difference. And if I could, in the time I have remaining, I'd like to just try to refocus the Court on the importance of what's at stake here. As we told you in our brief, our military leaders believe that it is imperative that we have officer corps that are not only diverse but capable of leading a diverse military, not only for effectiveness but for the very legitimacy of sending our troops into harm's way.","start":4994.93,"stop":5020.44,"duration":25.51}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But do you think that the African-American and Hispanic students who were admitted under the Top 10 Percent Plan make inferior officers when compared to those who were admitted under holistic review?","start":5020.44,"stop":5031.2,"duration":10.76}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I don't.","start":5031.2,"stop":5031.94,"duration":0.74},{"text":"Not at all. But I --","start":5031.94,"stop":5032.98,"duration":1.04}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think that the -- that the ROTC graduates from the University of Texas make superior officers to those who -- who graduate from, let's say, Texas A&M or Texas Tech?","start":5032.98,"stop":5043.425,"duration":10.45}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Here's what I think about that, Justice Alito: I think that we want to make sure -- and this military example is only one of the important interests here.","start":5043.425,"stop":5050.66,"duration":7.23},{"text":"But with respect to that, we want to make sure, not just that there are strong African-American and Hispanic candidates in that ROTC program, but that everybody who graduates from the ROTC program, University of Texas -- white, black, Asian, Hispanic -- everybody knows how to lead effectively in a -- in a diverse environment in which they're going to be leading diverse troops.","start":5050.66,"stop":5072.84,"duration":22.18},{"text":"That's the interest. And you can't achieve that --","start":5072.84,"stop":5074.33,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, that's certainly important, but to come back to my first question, is there anything to suggest that the top 10 percent students are less likely to enroll in ROTC or, when they do, they're not as good as the -- as the holistic admittees?","start":5074.33,"stop":5086.945,"duration":12.61}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":5086.945,"stop":5087.17,"duration":0.23},{"text":"I -- I think with respect to the University of Texas in particular.","start":5087.17,"stop":5090.03,"duration":2.86},{"text":"But I -- I'm also -- you know, what the Court is going to say in this case obviously is going to apply to -- eventually to every university in the country. And this is an important interest for the United States generally, that when you think about what's at stake here, that the -- the interest in ensuring that we have military officers who can lead a diverse military force is critical. The interest in having law enforcement officers who are not just diverse but who can operate effectively within every racial and ethnic community in highly charged situations is critically important. Corporate America has told you that having a -- a -- a workforce that is able to function effectively in diverse -- in diverse situations is critical. And what I would just say in conclusion is that these are the considered judgments of people who actually have the responsibility to ensure that the vital functions of the government protecting the country with the military and with law enforcement and the vital functions of commerce -- these are the people who actually have to make sure that those functions are carried out.","start":5090.03,"stop":5154.62,"duration":64.59},{"text":"And this is their considered judgment, and I submit it's -- it's worth considerable weight in your analysis. Thank you.","start":5154.62,"stop":5160.005,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"If -- if I can ask a question.","start":5160.005,"stop":5161.49,"duration":1.48}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, I'm sorry.","start":5161.49,"stop":5161.88,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":5161.88,"stop":5162.14,"duration":0.26},{"text":"I'm glad you said that.","start":5162.14,"stop":5163.29,"duration":1.15},{"text":"And -- and I -- this question will sound very nitpicky and detailed and -- compared to what you were talking about. And I agree.","start":5163.29,"stop":5170.5,"duration":7.21},{"text":"I notice that the briefs in this case are like the briefs in Grutter.","start":5170.5,"stop":5174.29,"duration":3.79},{"text":"And to me that does suggest that people in the universities and elsewhere are worried that we will, to use your colleague's expression, kill affirmative action through a death by a thousand cuts. We promised in Fisher I that we wouldn't. That opinion by seven people reflected no one's views perfectly.","start":5174.29,"stop":5196.76,"duration":22.47},{"text":"But that's what it says: Not fatal in fact. Okay.","start":5196.76,"stop":5201.89,"duration":5.13},{"text":"That's what I'm focusing on.","start":5201.89,"stop":5203.725,"duration":1.84},{"text":"It seems to me there are two parts to that, whether we have to send it back for another hearing or not. Part one you've dealt with.","start":5203.725,"stop":5211.61,"duration":7.88},{"text":"That's is there a need? A matter which Fisher I says we will give some but not complete deference to the University, and as you say, we have -- you went through that. There is a second part which I want you to address.","start":5211.61,"stop":5227.015,"duration":15.41},{"text":"The second part in Fisher, we said, there is no deference due the University.","start":5227.015,"stop":5233.525,"duration":6.51},{"text":"On this part it's called narrow tailoring. You heard your friend on the other side admit, he said, admit,","start":5233.525,"stop":5242.27,"duration":8.75},{"text":"maybe he believes it firmly, why use the word \"admit\"? -- he said that, in the plans of Grutter and the plans of Bakke, those were okay in respect to narrow tailoring because they did compare the students one after another and use race as a plus factor. Now, what is there in this record that will support the view that what Texas has done in respect to narrow tailoring is no worse than, perhaps even better than, what happened in Grutter or Bakke?","start":5242.27,"stop":5281.5,"duration":39.23}]},{"speakerName":"Donald B. Verrilli, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So I -- I would point Your Honor specifically to the declaration at pages 483a and 484 -- and 484a of the Joint Appendix of the admissions director, in which he explains the way race is considered in the University of Texas system.","start":5281.5,"stop":5297.43,"duration":15.93},{"text":"And that explanation says expressly, at page 483, that race is considered in exactly the same manner, and given exactly the same consideration as every other special circumstance's factor that the university considers as part of its holistic review. That -- I think that shows you that actually you know more about the way this program works than you did about the program that you affirmed in Grutter, and you have assurance based on that, and nothing in the record contradicts it that that's the way it operates.","start":5297.43,"stop":5328.515,"duration":31.09}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":5328.515,"stop":5328.9,"duration":0.38},{"text":"Thank you, General. Five minutes, Mr. Rein.","start":5328.9,"stop":5333.204,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Chief Justice. Let me first indicate that one of the questions that's been asked repeatedly, as -- well, what impact did the use of race actually have? Judge Garza -- and this is at Appendix 200 -- tried to make an estimate, because you can only make an estimate, because UT didn't know, and they don't know now.","start":5333.204,"stop":5356.53,"duration":23.33},{"text":"His estimate was that a very small number, and it -- it's in his opinion.","start":5356.53,"stop":5361.54,"duration":5.01},{"text":"It's -- it's not only by percentage, but it's by number, and that number is insignificant relative --","start":5361.54,"stop":5367.27,"duration":5.73}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you think -- do you think that change has to happen overnight? And do you think it's --","start":5367.27,"stop":5372.84,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":5372.84,"stop":5373.27,"duration":0.43},{"text":"Can I -- can I hear what you were about to say? What are those numbers? I was really curious to hear those numbers.","start":5373.27,"stop":5379.98,"duration":6.71}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"He assumed, at the outside, that any of the admits that were actually African-American or Hispanic outside the Top Ten, he said let me take that assumption and see what it would add.","start":5379.98,"stop":5391.2,"duration":11.22},{"text":"And he said it would constitute less than 1 percent and 2.5 percent, respectively, in -- of the entire 6,322-person case --","start":5391.2,"stop":5400.805,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"What are you reading from?","start":5400.805,"stop":5401.66,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"But he did not -- can I finish?","start":5401.66,"stop":5403.515,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you just tell me where you're reading from?","start":5403.515,"stop":5405.78,"duration":2.26}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"This is Appendix 250 to 251a.","start":5405.78,"stop":5409.77,"duration":3.99},{"text":"It is Judge Garza's original dissent.","start":5409.77,"stop":5411.98,"duration":2.21},{"text":"This is -- this is when -- and he repeated, essentially, the same point. But he calculated, and he made different assumptions, depending on how many of the admissions in the holistic program one would assume would be different because of race.","start":5411.98,"stop":5426.23,"duration":14.25},{"text":"Because no one knows, and that -- and that's part of this. And clearly, one -- and -- and -- I can read you these numbers, but you can read them yourselves. It's a very small number.","start":5426.23,"stop":5435.45,"duration":9.22},{"text":"And his most realistic estimate was that it would yield only 15 African-Americans and 40 Hispanic students in a class of 6,000.","start":5435.45,"stop":5444.43,"duration":8.98},{"text":"So we're talking about a very small effect, even with assumptions that -- that actually exist. You know, one point is it's small.","start":5444.43,"stop":5454.4,"duration":9.97},{"text":"The second point, equally important, is no one knew because they didn't study it. And then -- then we get the same point on this complementary, which was the big theme of the Fifth Circuit, oh, it's a necessary complement.","start":5454.4,"stop":5466.09,"duration":11.69},{"text":"What does that mean? One sense, you've got to have some plan if you're going to cap the Top Ten at 75 percent, so it's necessary to do something.","start":5466.09,"stop":5473.6,"duration":7.51},{"text":"But that doesn't make it a necessary complement. When you really look what the Fifth Circuit said, they said it's based on two assumptions: One, the Top Ten are drawn from these minority high schools. Where did they come up with that? They never studied the pattern of the Top Ten admits. How do you know that a Hispanic or an African-American student can't be in the Top Ten at what they call an integrated, high-performing high school? That's a stereotypical assumption.","start":5473.6,"stop":5500.21,"duration":26.61}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I -- I -- what you're saying, basically, is, is this is what the Fifth Circuit concluded and which the school basically agrees, okay? If you don't consider race, then holistic percentage, whatever it is, is going to be virtually all white.","start":5500.21,"stop":5519.78,"duration":19.57}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is incorrect.","start":5519.78,"stop":5520.71,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All white.","start":5520.71,"stop":5521.12,"duration":0.41}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"And that is an assumption --","start":5521.12,"stop":5522.32,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"And to say -- no --","start":5522.32,"stop":5523.06,"duration":0.74}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that has no basis in this record.","start":5523.06,"stop":5524.56,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, but there is --","start":5524.56,"stop":5524.95,"duration":0.39}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a stereotypical --","start":5524.95,"stop":5526.44,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's not --","start":5526.44,"stop":5527.23,"duration":0.79}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"-- assumption.","start":5527.23,"stop":5527.89,"duration":0.66},{"text":"That is what it is.","start":5527.89,"stop":5528.56,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not, because the reality --","start":5528.56,"stop":5529.74,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"With all deference --","start":5529.74,"stop":5530.5,"duration":0.76}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- that Justice --","start":5530.5,"stop":5530.99,"duration":0.49}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Rein --","start":5530.99,"stop":5531.61,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- Alito wants to rely on. Let me finish my point. He's right.","start":5531.61,"stop":5536.17,"duration":4.56},{"text":"For their educational needs, there are competing criteria.","start":5536.17,"stop":5541.41,"duration":5.24},{"text":"They need to keep a certain SAT, or whatever that's called, AI index, that has to be high because of the quality they want to keep the school at.","start":5541.41,"stop":5552.69,"duration":11.28},{"text":"That does discriminate against blacks on some levels, because the difference in numbers are high. So if you have something like this, you're -- what you're saying, basically, is, and what he's proposing, is change your educational needs across the board, and focus in only on race, and make sure that your school is black, Hispanic, or whatever on numbers that are going to reduce its educational quality. That's basically what you're arguing, isn't it?","start":5552.69,"stop":5590.82,"duration":38.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":5590.82,"stop":5592.345,"duration":1.53},{"text":"And -- and to be fair, I mean, the first thing I was just pointing out is that to get to the conclusion of the Fifth Circuit, you have to first assume the pattern of admits in the Top Ten, where they come from, which was never established in the record, never studied. And the second is that you have to assume that those coming from -- all students coming from these integrated, high-performing high schools don't include, in their Top 10 percent, any minority.","start":5592.345,"stop":5618.23,"duration":25.88}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Why? What we know is --","start":5618.23,"stop":5619.76,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That's what he assumes.","start":5619.76,"stop":5620.43,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- the school doesn't have enough --","start":5620.43,"stop":5622.095,"duration":1.66}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Sotomayor --","start":5622.095,"stop":5623.14,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"-- no matter what it does, it doesn't have enough numbers of black people.","start":5623.14,"stop":5627.27,"duration":4.13}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"That -- that comes back to the fundamental point. If we're just talking numbers, then you have to show the compelling need for more numbers, so that -- one of the reasons for defining your compelling need is that you have to then look at necessity in terms of the need. So as in Grutter, what they said was we have insufficient numbers of minorities to provoke the appropriate dialogue.","start":5627.27,"stop":5650.4,"duration":23.13},{"text":"When we look at the class as a whole, we think we can do better if we introduce different points of view.","start":5650.4,"stop":5655.34,"duration":4.94},{"text":"It's very individualized; it's a small class. So you can then say, increasing numbers -- which they were certainly after, you know, from three to 14 -- will meet that compelling need. Since they never bothered to administer, you know, to define the needs, it's really hard to say what they were after and why numbers would or would not satisfy, and whether the numbers they were generating, which included 15 percent of the so-called holistic admits so it wasn't all white enterprise, why that wouldn't work. The key point is, you have to come to the Court with the record.","start":5655.34,"stop":5690.39,"duration":35.05},{"text":"You can't make it up later, because that would say do what you want, and when the time comes, make it up.","start":5690.39,"stop":5696.47,"duration":6.08},{"text":"That's not -- no way to litigate. And in this case they said, we're ready for summary judgment; we've put in everything we need.","start":5696.47,"stop":5703.35,"duration":6.88},{"text":"If you look at their specific proffers -- and the court of appeals, they said they wanted to take discovery.","start":5703.35,"stop":5707.62,"duration":4.27},{"text":"And even Judge Higginbotham, their best friend, said, from who? What does Ms. Fisher know about this? What are you going to take discovery about? And he found no need in this Court, all they say is, we'd like to reiterate the benefits of diversity, but those were accepted, and we'd like a few testimonials about students admitted holistically without knowing whether they were the beneficiaries of the race or not.","start":5707.62,"stop":5726.98,"duration":19.36}]},{"speakerName":"Bert W. Rein","textObjs":[{"text":"You can't -- can't litigate that way. Thank you, Your Honor.","start":5726.98,"stop":5729.32,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel. The case is submitted.","start":5729.32,"stop":0,"duration":-5729.32}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Dec 9, 2015","petitioner":"Abigail Noel Fisher","respondent":"University of Texas at Austin, et al.","docket":"14-981","citation":"579US_(2016)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/579/14-981","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit","grantedOn":"Jun 29, 2015","decidedOn":"Jun 23, 2016"}